<DIV class=3D"section" id=3D"introduction">
<H1><A name=3D"introduction" class=3D"toc-backref" =
href=3D"https://sysbio.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/usersguide/#id17">1=A0=A0=A0=
Introduction</A></H1>
<P>The purpose of the <A class=3D"reference" =
href=3D"http://cens.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/">F2PY</A>=20
--<EM>Fortran to Python interface generator</EM>-- project is to provide =
a=20
connection between Python and Fortran languages.  F2PY is a <A =
class=3D"reference"=20
href=3D"http://www.python.org/">Python</A> package (with a command line =
tool <TT=20
class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">f2py</SPAN></TT> and a module <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">f2py2e</SPAN></TT>) that facilitates creating/building =
Python C/API=20
extension modules that make it possible</P>
<UL class=3D"simple">
  <LI>to call Fortran 77/90/95 external subroutines and Fortran 90/95 =
module=20
  subroutines as well as C functions;</LI>
  <LI>to access Fortran 77 <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">COMMON</SPAN></TT> blocks and Fortran 90/95 module data, =
including=20
  allocatable arrays</LI></UL>
<P>from Python. See <A class=3D"reference" =
href=3D"http://cens.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/">F2PY</A>=20
web site for more information and installation instructions.</P></DIV>
<DIV class=3D"section" id=3D"three-ways-to-wrap-getting-started">
<H1><A name=3D"three-ways-to-wrap-getting-started" class=3D"toc-backref" =
href=3D"https://sysbio.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/usersguide/#id18">2=A0=A0=A0=
Three=20
ways to wrap - getting started</A></H1>
<P>Wrapping Fortran or C functions to Python using F2PY consists of the
 following steps:</P>
<UL class=3D"simple">
  <LI>Creating the so-called signature file that contains descriptions =
of
   wrappers to Fortran or C functions, also called as signatures of the
   functions. In the case of Fortran routines, F2PY can create initial =
signature=20
  file by scanning Fortran source codes and catching all relevant =
information=20
  needed to create wrapper functions.</LI>
  <LI>Optionally, F2PY created signature files can be edited to optimize
   wrappers functions, make them "smarter" and more "Pythonic".</LI>
  <LI>F2PY reads a signature file and writes a Python C/API module =
containing
   Fortran/C/Python bindings.</LI>
  <LI>F2PY compiles all sources and builds an extension module =
containing the=20
  wrappers. In building extension modules, F2PY uses <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">scipy_distutils</SPAN></TT> that supports a number of =
Fortran=20
  77/90/95 compilers, including Gnu, Intel, Sun Fortre, SGI MIPSpro, =
Absoft,=20
  NAG, Compaq etc. compilers.</LI></UL>
<P>Depending on a particular situation, these steps can be carried out =
either by=20
just in one command or step-by-step, some steps can be ommited or =
combined with=20
others.</P>
<P>Below I'll describe three typical approaches of using F2PY. The =
following <A=20
class=3D"reference"=20
href=3D"https://sysbio.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/usersguide/fib1.f">example =
Fortran=20
77 code</A> will be used for illustration:</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">C FILE: FIB1.F=0A=
      SUBROUTINE FIB(A,N)=0A=
C=0A=
C     CALCULATE FIRST N FIBONACCI NUMBERS=0A=
C=0A=
      INTEGER N=0A=
      REAL*8 A(N)=0A=
      DO I=3D1,N=0A=
         IF (I.EQ.1) THEN=0A=
            A(I) =3D 0.0D0=0A=
         ELSEIF (I.EQ.2) THEN=0A=
            A(I) =3D 1.0D0=0A=
         ELSE =0A=
            A(I) =3D A(I-1) + A(I-2)=0A=
         ENDIF=0A=
      ENDDO=0A=
      END=0A=
C END FILE FIB1.F=0A=
=0A=
</PRE>
<DIV class=3D"section" id=3D"the-quick-way">
<H2><A name=3D"the-quick-way" class=3D"toc-backref" =
href=3D"https://sysbio.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/usersguide/#id19">2.1=A0=A0=
=A0The=20
quick way</A></H2>
<P>The quickest way to wrap the Fortran subroutine <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">FIB</SPAN></TT> to Python is to run</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">f2py -c fib1.f -m fib1=0A=
</PRE>
<P>This command builds (see <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">-c</SPAN></TT>=20
flag, execute <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">f2py</SPAN></TT> =
without
 arguments to see the explanation of command line options) an extension =
module=20
<TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">fib1.so</SPAN></TT> (see <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">-m</SPAN></TT> flag) to the current directory. Now, in =
Python the=20
Fortran subroutine <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">FIB</SPAN></TT> is=20
accessible via <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">fib1.fib</SPAN></TT>:</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">&gt;&gt;&gt; import Numeric=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; import fib1=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; print fib1.fib.__doc__=0A=
fib - Function signature:=0A=
  fib(a,[n])=0A=
Required arguments:=0A=
  a : input rank-1 array('d') with bounds (n)=0A=
Optional arguments:=0A=
  n :=3D len(a) input int=0A=
=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; a=3DNumeric.zeros(8,'d')=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; fib1.fib(a)=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; print a=0A=
[  0.   1.   1.   2.   3.   5.   8.  13.]=0A=
</PRE>
<DIV class=3D"topic">
<P class=3D"topic-title">Comments</P>
<UL>
  <LI>
  <P class=3D"first">Note that F2PY found that the second argument <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">n</SPAN></TT> is the dimension of the first array =
argument <TT=20
  class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">a</SPAN></TT>. Since by default =
all
   arguments are input-only arguments, F2PY concludes that <TT=20
  class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">n</SPAN></TT> can be optional =
with the=20
  default value <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">len(a)</SPAN></TT>.</P></LI>
  <LI>
  <P class=3D"first">One can use different values for optional <TT=20
  class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">n</SPAN></TT>:</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">&gt;&gt;&gt; a1=3DNumeric.zeros(8,'d')=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; fib1.fib(a1,6)=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; print a1=0A=
[ 0.  1.  1.  2.  3.  5.  0.  0.]=0A=
</PRE>
  <P>but an exception is raised when it is incompatible with the input =
array <TT=20
  class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">a</SPAN></TT>:</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">&gt;&gt;&gt; fib1.fib(a,10)=0A=
fib:n=3D10=0A=
Traceback (most recent call last):=0A=
  File "&lt;stdin&gt;", line 1, in ?=0A=
fib.error: (len(a)&gt;=3Dn) failed for 1st keyword n=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; =0A=
</PRE>
  <P>This demonstrates one of the useful features in F2PY, that it, F2PY =

  implements basic compatibility checks between related arguments in =
order to=20
  avoid any unexpected crashes.</P></LI>
  <LI>
  <P class=3D"first">When a Numeric array, that is Fortran contiguous =
and has a=20
  typecode corresponding to presumed Fortran type, is used as an input =
array
   argument, then its C pointer is directly passed to Fortran.</P>
  <P>Otherwise F2PY makes a contiguous copy (with a proper typecode) of =
the=20
  input array and passes C pointer of the copy to Fortran subroutine. As =
a=20
  result, any possible changes to the (copy of) input array have no =
effect to=20
  the original argument, as demonstrated below:</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">&gt;&gt;&gt; a=3DNumeric.ones(8,'i')=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; fib1.fib(a)=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; print a=0A=
[1 1 1 1 1 1 1 1]=0A=
</PRE>
  <P>Clearly, this is not an expected behaviour. The fact that the above =
example=20
  worked with <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">typecode=3D'd'</SPAN></TT> is=20
  considered accidental.</P>
  <P>F2PY provides <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">intent(inplace)</SPAN></TT> attribute that would modify =
the=20
  attributes of an input array so that any changes made by Fortran =
routine will=20
  be effective also in input argument. For example, if one specifies <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">intent(inplace)</SPAN> <SPAN class=3D"pre">a</SPAN></TT> =
(see below,=20
  how), then the example above would read:</P>
  <BLOCKQUOTE>
<PRE class=3D"doctest-block">&gt;&gt;&gt; a=3DNumeric.ones(8,'i')=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; fib1.fib(a)=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; print a=0A=
[  0.   1.   1.   2.   3.   5.   8.  13.]=0A=
</PRE></BLOCKQUOTE>
  <P>However, the recommended way to get changes made by Fortran =
subroutine back=20
  to python is to use <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">intent(out)</SPAN></TT> attribute. It is more efficient =
and a=20
  cleaner solution.</P></LI>
  <LI>
  <P class=3D"first">The usage of <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">fib1.fib</SPAN></TT> in Python is very similar to using =
<TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">FIB</SPAN></TT> in Fortran. However, using <EM>in =
situ</EM> output=20
  arguments in Python indicates a poor style as there is no safety =
mechanism in=20
  Python with respect to wrong argument types. When using Fortran or C,=20
  compilers naturally discover any type mismatches during compile time =
but in=20
  Python the types must be checked in runtime. So, using <EM>in =
situ</EM> output=20
  arguments in Python may cause difficult to find bugs, not to mention =
that the=20
  codes will be less readable when all required type checks are=20
  implemented.</P></LI></UL>
<P>Though the demonstrated way of wrapping Fortran routines to Python is =
very=20
straightforward, it has several drawbacks (see the comments above).  =
These=20
drawbacks are due to the fact that there is no way that F2PY can =
determine what=20
is the acctual intention of one or the other argument, is it input or =
output=20
argument, or both, or something else. So, F2PY conservatively assumes =
that all=20
arguments are input arguments by default.</P>
<P>However, there are ways (see below) how to "teach" F2PY about the =
true=20
intentions (among other things) of function arguments; and then F2PY is =
able to=20
generate more Pythonic (more explicit, easier to use, and less error =
prone)=20
wrappers to Fortran functions.</P></DIV></DIV>
<DIV class=3D"section" id=3D"the-smart-way">
<H2><A name=3D"the-smart-way" class=3D"toc-backref" =
href=3D"https://sysbio.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/usersguide/#id20">2.2=A0=A0=
=A0The=20
smart way</A></H2>
<P>Let's apply the steps of wrapping Fortran functions to Python one by =
one.</P>
<UL>
  <LI>
  <P class=3D"first">First, we create a signature file from <TT=20
  class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">fib1.f</SPAN></TT> by =
running</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">f2py fib1.f -m fib2 -h fib1.pyf=0A=
</PRE>
  <P>The signature file is saved to <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">fib1.pyf</SPAN></TT> (see <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">-h</SPAN></TT> flag) and its contents is shown =
below.</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">!    -*- f90 -*-=0A=
python module fib2 ! in =0A=
    interface  ! in :fib2=0A=
        subroutine fib(a,n) ! in :fib2:fib1.f=0A=
            real*8 dimension(n) :: a=0A=
            integer optional,check(len(a)&gt;=3Dn),depend(a) :: =
n=3Dlen(a)=0A=
        end subroutine fib=0A=
    end interface =0A=
end python module fib2=0A=
=0A=
! This file was auto-generated with f2py (version:2.28.198-1366).=0A=
! See http://cens.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/=0A=
=0A=
</PRE></LI>
  <LI>
  <P class=3D"first">Next, we'll teach F2PY that the argument <TT=20
  class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">n</SPAN></TT> is a input =
argument (use <TT=20
  class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">intent(in)</SPAN></TT> =
attribute) and that=20
  the result, i.e. the contents of <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">a</SPAN></TT> after calling Fortran function <TT=20
  class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">FIB</SPAN></TT>, should be =
returned to=20
  Python (use <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">intent(out)</SPAN></TT>=20
  attribute). In addition, an array <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">a</SPAN></TT> should be created dynamically using the =
size given=20
  by the input argument <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">n</SPAN></TT> (use=20
  <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">depend(n)</SPAN></TT> =
attribute to=20
  indicate dependence relation).</P>
  <P>The content of a modified version of <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">fib1.pyf</SPAN></TT> (saved as <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">fib2.pyf</SPAN></TT>)=20
  is as follows:</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">!    -*- f90 -*-=0A=
python module fib2 =0A=
    interface=0A=
        subroutine fib(a,n)=0A=
            real*8 dimension(n),intent(out),depend(n) :: a=0A=
            integer intent(in) :: n=0A=
        end subroutine fib=0A=
    end interface =0A=
end python module fib2=0A=
=0A=
</PRE></LI>
  <LI>
  <P class=3D"first">And finally, we build the extension module by =
running</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">f2py -c fib2.pyf fib1.f=0A=
</PRE></LI></UL>
<P>In Python:</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">&gt;&gt;&gt; import fib2=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; print fib2.fib.__doc__=0A=
fib - Function signature:=0A=
  a =3D fib(n)=0A=
Required arguments:=0A=
  n : input int=0A=
Return objects:=0A=
  a : rank-1 array('d') with bounds (n)=0A=
=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; print fib2.fib(8)     =0A=
[  0.   1.   1.   2.   3.   5.   8.  13.]=0A=
</PRE>
<DIV class=3D"topic">
<P class=3D"topic-title">Comments</P>
<UL class=3D"simple">
  <LI>Clearly, the signature of <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">fib2.fib</SPAN></TT> now corresponds to the intention of =
Fortran=20
  subroutine <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">FIB</SPAN></TT> =
more closely:=20
  given the number <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">n</SPAN></TT>, <TT=20
  class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">fib2.fib</SPAN></TT> returns the =
first <TT=20
  class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">n</SPAN></TT> Fibonacci numbers =
as a Numeric=20
  array. Also, the new Python signature <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">fib2.fib</SPAN></TT> rules out any surprises that we =
experienced=20
  with <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">fib1.fib</SPAN></TT>.</LI>
  <LI>Note that by default using single <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">intent(out)</SPAN></TT> also implies <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">intent(hide)</SPAN></TT>. Argument that has <TT=20
  class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">intent(hide)</SPAN></TT> =
attribute
   specified, will not be listed in the argument list of a wrapper
 function.</LI></UL></DIV></DIV>
<DIV class=3D"section" id=3D"the-quick-and-smart-way">
<H2><A name=3D"the-quick-and-smart-way" class=3D"toc-backref" =
href=3D"https://sysbio.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/usersguide/#id21">2.3=A0=A0=
=A0The=20
quick and smart way</A></H2>
<P>The "smart way" of wrapping Fortran functions, as explained above, is
 suitable for wrapping (e.g. third party) Fortran codes for which =
modifications=20
to their source codes are not desirable nor even possible.</P>
<P>However, if editing Fortran codes is acceptable, then the generation =
of an=20
intermediate signature file can be skipped in most cases. Namely, F2PY =
specific=20
attributes can be inserted directly to Fortran source codes using the =
so-called=20
F2PY directive. A F2PY directive defines special comment lines (starting =
with=20
<TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">Cf2py</SPAN></TT>, for =
example) which are=20
ignored by Fortran compilers but F2PY interprets them as normal =
lines.</P>
<P>Here is shown a <A class=3D"reference" =
href=3D"https://sysbio.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/usersguide/fib3.f">modified=
=20
version of the example Fortran code</A>, saved as <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">fib3.f</SPAN></TT>:</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">C FILE: FIB3.F=0A=
      SUBROUTINE FIB(A,N)=0A=
C=0A=
C     CALCULATE FIRST N FIBONACCI NUMBERS=0A=
C=0A=
      INTEGER N=0A=
      REAL*8 A(N)=0A=
Cf2py intent(in) n=0A=
Cf2py intent(out) a=0A=
Cf2py depend(n) a=0A=
      DO I=3D1,N=0A=
         IF (I.EQ.1) THEN=0A=
            A(I) =3D 0.0D0=0A=
         ELSEIF (I.EQ.2) THEN=0A=
            A(I) =3D 1.0D0=0A=
         ELSE =0A=
            A(I) =3D A(I-1) + A(I-2)=0A=
         ENDIF=0A=
      ENDDO=0A=
      END=0A=
C END FILE FIB3.F=0A=
=0A=
</PRE>
<P>Building the extension module can be now carried out in one =
command:</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">f2py -c -m fib3 fib3.f=0A=
</PRE>
<P>Notice that the resulting wrapper to <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">FIB</SPAN></TT> is as "smart" as in previous case:</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">&gt;&gt;&gt; import fib3=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; print fib3.fib.__doc__=0A=
fib - Function signature:=0A=
  a =3D fib(n)=0A=
Required arguments:=0A=
  n : input int=0A=
Return objects:=0A=
  a : rank-1 array('d') with bounds (n)=0A=
=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; print fib3.fib(8)     =0A=
[  0.   1.   1.   2.   3.   5.   8.  13.]=0A=
</PRE></DIV></DIV>
<DIV class=3D"section" id=3D"signature-file">
<H1><A name=3D"signature-file" class=3D"toc-backref" =
href=3D"https://sysbio.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/usersguide/#id22">3=A0=A0=A0=
Signature=20
file</A></H1>
<P>The syntax specification for signature files (.pyf files) is borrowed =
from=20
the Fortran 90/95 language specification. Almost all Fortran 90/95 =
standard=20
constructs are understood, both in free and fixed format (recall that =
Fortran 77=20
is a subset of Fortran 90/95). F2PY introduces also some extensions to =
Fortran=20
90/95 language specification that help designing Fortran to Python =
interface,=20
make it more "Pythonic".</P>
<P>Signature files may contain arbitrary Fortran code (so that Fortran =
codes can=20
be considered as signature files). F2PY silently ignores Fortran =
constructs that=20
are irrelevant for creating the interface. However, this includes also =
syntax=20
errors. So, be careful not making ones;-).</P>
<P>In general, the contents of signature files is case-sensitive.  When =
scanning=20
Fortran codes and writing a signature file, F2PY lowers all cases =
automatically=20
except in multi-line blocks or when <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">--no-lower</SPAN></TT> option is used.</P>
<P>The syntax of signature files is overvied below.</P>
<DIV class=3D"section" id=3D"python-module-block">
<H2><A name=3D"python-module-block" class=3D"toc-backref" =
href=3D"https://sysbio.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/usersguide/#id23">3.1=A0=A0=
=A0Python=20
module block</A></H2>
<P>A signature file may contain one (recommended) or more <TT=20
class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">python</SPAN> <SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">module</SPAN></TT> blocks.  <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">python</SPAN> <SPAN class=3D"pre">module</SPAN></TT> block =
describes=20
the contents of a Python/C extension module <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">&lt;modulename&gt;module.c</SPAN></TT>=20
that F2PY generates.</P>
<P>Exception: if <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">&lt;modulename&gt;</SPAN></TT> contains a substring <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">__user__</SPAN></TT>, then the corresponding <TT=20
class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">python</SPAN> <SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">module</SPAN></TT> block describes the signatures of =
so-called=20
call-back functions (see <A class=3D"reference" =
href=3D"https://sysbio.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/usersguide/#call-back-argum=
ents">Call-back=20
arguments</A>).</P>
<P>A <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">python</SPAN> <SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">module</SPAN></TT> block has the following structure:</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">python module &lt;modulename&gt;=0A=
  [&lt;usercode statement&gt;]...=0A=
  [=0A=
  interface=0A=
    &lt;usercode statement&gt;=0A=
    &lt;Fortran block data signatures&gt;=0A=
    &lt;Fortran/C routine signatures&gt;=0A=
  end [interface]=0A=
  ]...=0A=
  [=0A=
  interface=0A=
    module &lt;F90 modulename&gt;=0A=
      [&lt;F90 module data type declarations&gt;]=0A=
      [&lt;F90 module routine signatures&gt;]=0A=
    end [module [&lt;F90 modulename&gt;]]=0A=
  end [interface]=0A=
  ]...=0A=
end [python module [&lt;modulename&gt;]]=0A=
</PRE>
<P>Here brackets <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">[]</SPAN></TT> indicate a=20
optional part, dots <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">...</SPAN></TT>=20
indicate one or more of a previous part. So, <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">[]...</SPAN></TT>=20
reads zero or more of a previous part.</P></DIV>
<DIV class=3D"section" id=3D"fortran-c-routine-signatures">
<H2><A name=3D"fortran-c-routine-signatures" class=3D"toc-backref" =
href=3D"https://sysbio.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/usersguide/#id24">3.2=A0=A0=
=A0Fortran/C=20
routine signatures</A></H2>
<P>The signature of a Fortran routine has the following structure:</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">[&lt;typespec&gt;] function | subroutine =
&lt;routine name&gt; \=0A=
              [ ( [&lt;arguments&gt;] ) ] [ result ( &lt;entityname&gt; =
) ]=0A=
  [&lt;argument/variable type declarations&gt;]=0A=
  [&lt;argument/variable attribute statements&gt;]=0A=
  [&lt;use statements&gt;]=0A=
  [&lt;common block statements&gt;]=0A=
  [&lt;other statements&gt;]=0A=
end [ function | subroutine [&lt;routine name&gt;] ]=0A=
</PRE>
<P>From a Fortran routine signature F2PY generates a Python/C extension =
function=20
that has the following signature:</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">def &lt;routine name&gt;(&lt;required =
arguments&gt;[,&lt;optional arguments&gt;]):=0A=
     ...=0A=
     return &lt;return variables&gt;=0A=
</PRE>
<P>The signature of a Fortran block data has the following =
structure:</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">block data [ &lt;block data name&gt; ]=0A=
  [&lt;variable type declarations&gt;]=0A=
  [&lt;variable attribute statements&gt;]=0A=
  [&lt;use statements&gt;]=0A=
  [&lt;common block statements&gt;]=0A=
  [&lt;include statements&gt;]=0A=
end [ block data [&lt;block data name&gt;] ]=0A=
</PRE>
<DIV class=3D"section" id=3D"type-declarations">
<H3><A name=3D"type-declarations" class=3D"toc-backref" =
href=3D"https://sysbio.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/usersguide/#id25">3.2.1=A0=A0=
=A0Type=20
declarations</A></H3>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  <P>The definition of the <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">&lt;argument/variable</SPAN> <SPAN =
class=3D"pre">type</SPAN> <SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">declaration&gt;</SPAN></TT> part is</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">&lt;typespec&gt; [ [&lt;attrspec&gt;] :: ] =
&lt;entitydecl&gt;=0A=
</PRE>
  <P>where</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">&lt;typespec&gt; :=3D byte | character =
[&lt;charselector&gt;] =0A=
           | complex [&lt;kindselector&gt;] | real [&lt;kindselector&gt;]=0A=
           | double complex | double precision =0A=
           | integer [&lt;kindselector&gt;] | logical =
[&lt;kindselector&gt;]=0A=
=0A=
&lt;charselector&gt; :=3D * &lt;charlen&gt; =0A=
               | ( [len=3D] &lt;len&gt; [ , [kind=3D] &lt;kind&gt;] )=0A=
               | ( kind=3D &lt;kind&gt; [ , len=3D &lt;len&gt; ] )=0A=
&lt;kindselector&gt; :=3D * &lt;intlen&gt; | ( [kind=3D] &lt;kind&gt; )=0A=
=0A=
&lt;entitydecl&gt; :=3D &lt;name&gt; [ [ * &lt;charlen&gt; ] [ ( =
&lt;arrayspec&gt; ) ] =0A=
                      | [ ( &lt;arrayspec&gt; ) ] * &lt;charlen&gt; ]=0A=
                     | [ / &lt;init_expr&gt; / | =3D &lt;init_expr&gt; ] =
\=0A=
                       [ , &lt;entitydecl&gt; ]=0A=
</PRE>
  <P>and</P>
  <UL class=3D"simple">
    <LI><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">&lt;attrspec&gt;</SPAN></TT> is a=20
    comma separated list of <A class=3D"reference" =
href=3D"https://sysbio.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/usersguide/#attributes">att=
ributes</A>;</LI>
    <LI><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">&lt;arrayspec&gt;</SPAN></TT> is a=20
    comma separated list of dimension bounds;</LI>
    <LI><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">&lt;init_expr&gt;</SPAN></TT> is a=20
    <A class=3D"reference" =
href=3D"https://sysbio.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/usersguide/#c-expressions">=
C=20
    expression</A>.</LI>
    <LI><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">&lt;intlen&gt;</SPAN></TT> may be=20
    negative integer for <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
    class=3D"pre">integer</SPAN></TT> type specifications. In such cases =
<TT=20
    class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">integer*&lt;negintlen&gt;</SPAN></TT>=20
    represents unsigned C integers.</LI></UL></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>If an argument has no <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">&lt;argument</SPAN> <SPAN class=3D"pre">type</SPAN> =
<SPAN class=3D"pre">declaration&gt;</SPAN></TT>,=20
  its type is determined by applying <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">implicit</SPAN></TT> rules to its =
name.</BLOCKQUOTE></DIV>
<DIV class=3D"section" id=3D"statements">
<H3><A name=3D"statements" class=3D"toc-backref" =
href=3D"https://sysbio.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/usersguide/#id26">3.2.2=A0=A0=
=A0Statements</A></H3>
<P>Attribute statements:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>The <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">&lt;argument/variable</SPAN> <SPAN =
class=3D"pre">attribute</SPAN>=20
  <SPAN class=3D"pre">statement&gt;</SPAN></TT> is <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">&lt;argument/variable</SPAN> <SPAN =
class=3D"pre">type</SPAN> <SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">declaration&gt;</SPAN></TT> without <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">&lt;typespec&gt;</SPAN></TT>. In addition, in an =
attribute=20
  statement one cannot use other attributes, also <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">&lt;entitydecl&gt;</SPAN></TT> can be only a list of=20
names.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Use statements:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  <P>The definition of the <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">&lt;use</SPAN>=20
  <SPAN class=3D"pre">statement&gt;</SPAN></TT> part is</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">use &lt;modulename&gt; [ , =
&lt;rename_list&gt; | , ONLY : &lt;only_list&gt; ]=0A=
</PRE>
  <P>where</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">&lt;rename_list&gt; :=3D &lt;local_name&gt; =
=3D&gt; &lt;use_name&gt; [ , &lt;rename_list&gt; ]=0A=
</PRE>
  <P>Currently F2PY uses <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">use</SPAN></TT>=20
  statement only for linking call-back modules and <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">external</SPAN></TT> arguments (call-back functions), =
see  <A=20
  class=3D"reference" =
href=3D"https://sysbio.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/usersguide/#call-back-argum=
ents">Call-back=20
  arguments</A>.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Common block statements:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  <P>The definition of the <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">&lt;common</SPAN> <SPAN class=3D"pre">block</SPAN> <SPAN =

  class=3D"pre">statement&gt;</SPAN></TT> part is</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">common / &lt;common name&gt; / =
&lt;shortentitydecl&gt;=0A=
</PRE>
  <P>where</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">&lt;shortentitydecl&gt; :=3D &lt;name&gt; [ =
( &lt;arrayspec&gt; ) ] [ , &lt;shortentitydecl&gt; ]=0A=
</PRE>
  <P>One <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">python</SPAN> <SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">module</SPAN></TT> block should not contain two or more =
<TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">common</SPAN></TT> blocks with the same name. Otherwise, =
the=20
  latter ones are ignored. The types of variables in <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">&lt;shortentitydecl&gt;</SPAN></TT> are defined using =
<TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">&lt;argument</SPAN> <SPAN class=3D"pre">type</SPAN> =
<SPAN class=3D"pre">declarations&gt;</SPAN></TT>.=20
  Note that the corresponding <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">&lt;argument</SPAN> <SPAN class=3D"pre">type</SPAN> =
<SPAN class=3D"pre">declarations&gt;</SPAN></TT>=20
  may contain array specifications; then you don't need to specify these =
in <TT=20
  class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">&lt;shortentitydecl&gt;</SPAN></TT>.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Other statements:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  <P>The <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">&lt;other</SPAN> =
<SPAN class=3D"pre">statement&gt;</SPAN></TT>=20
  part refers to any other Fortran language constructs that are not =
described=20
  above. F2PY ignores most of them except</P>
  <UL class=3D"simple">
    <LI><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">call</SPAN></TT> =
statements and=20
    function calls of <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">external</SPAN></TT>=20
    arguments (<A class=3D"reference" =
href=3D"https://sysbio.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/usersguide/#external">more =

    details</A>?);</LI></UL></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  <UL>
    <LI>
    <P class=3D"first"><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">include</SPAN></TT>=20
    statements</P>
    <BLOCKQUOTE>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">include '&lt;filename&gt;'=0A=
include "&lt;filename&gt;"=0A=
</PRE>
      <P>If a file <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">&lt;filename&gt;</SPAN></TT> does not exist, the <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">include</SPAN></TT> statement is ignored. Otherwise, =
the file=20
      <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">&lt;filename&gt;</SPAN></TT> is
       included to a signature file.  <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">include</SPAN></TT> statements can be used in any =
part of a=20
      signature file, also outside the Fortran/C routine signature=20
    blocks.</P></BLOCKQUOTE></LI>
    <LI>
    <P class=3D"first"><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">implicit</SPAN></TT>=20
    statements</P>
    <BLOCKQUOTE>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">implicit none=0A=
implicit &lt;list of implicit maps&gt;=0A=
</PRE>
      <P>where</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">&lt;implicit map&gt; :=3D &lt;typespec&gt; =
( &lt;list of letters or range of letters&gt; )=0A=
</PRE>
      <P>Implicit rules are used to deterimine the type specification of =
a=20
      variable (from the first-letter of its name) if the variable is =
not=20
      defined using <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">&lt;variable</SPAN>=20
      <SPAN class=3D"pre">type</SPAN> <SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">declaration&gt;</SPAN></TT>.  Default implicit rule =
is given=20
      by</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">implicit real (a-h,o-z,$_), integer (i-m)=0A=
</PRE></BLOCKQUOTE></LI>
    <LI>
    <P class=3D"first"><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">entry</SPAN></TT>=20
    statements</P>
    <BLOCKQUOTE>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">entry &lt;entry name&gt; =
[([&lt;arguments&gt;])]=0A=
</PRE>
      <P>F2PY generates wrappers to all entry names using the signature =
of the=20
      routine block.</P>
      <P>Tip: <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">entry</SPAN></TT> statement=20
      can be used to describe the signature of an arbitrary routine =
allowing=20
      F2PY to generate a number of wrappers from only one routine block=20
      signature. There are few restrictions while doing this: <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">fortranname</SPAN></TT> cannot be used, <TT=20
      class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">callstatement</SPAN></TT> =
and <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">callprotoargument</SPAN></TT> can be used only if =
they are=20
      valid for all entry routines, etc.</P></BLOCKQUOTE></LI></UL>
  <P>In addition, F2PY introduces the following statements:</P>
  <UL>
    <LI>
    <DL class=3D"first">
      <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">threadsafe</SPAN></TT></DT>
      <DD>
      <P class=3D"first last">Use <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">Py_BEGIN_ALLOW_THREADS</SPAN> <SPAN =
class=3D"pre">..</SPAN>=20
      <SPAN class=3D"pre">Py_END_ALLOW_THREADS</SPAN></TT> block around =
the call=20
      to Fortran/C function.</P></DD></DL></LI>
    <LI>
    <DL class=3D"first">
      <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">callstatement</SPAN> =
<SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">&lt;C-expr|multi-line</SPAN> <SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">block&gt;</SPAN></TT></DT>
      <DD>
      <P class=3D"first last">Replace F2PY generated call statement to =
Fortran/C=20
      function with <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">&lt;C-expr|multi-line</SPAN> <SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">block&gt;</SPAN></TT>. The wrapped Fortran/C =
function is=20
      available as <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">(*f2py_func)</SPAN></TT>. To raise an exception, set =
<TT=20
      class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">f2py_success</SPAN> <SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">=3D</SPAN> <SPAN class=3D"pre">0</SPAN></TT> in <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">&lt;C-expr|multi-line</SPAN> <SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">block&gt;</SPAN></TT>.</P></DD></DL></LI>
    <LI>
    <DL class=3D"first">
      <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">callprotoargument</SPAN> <SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">&lt;C-typespecs&gt;</SPAN></TT></DT>
      <DD>
      <P class=3D"first">When <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">callstatement</SPAN></TT> statement is used then =
F2PY may not
       generate proper prototypes for Fortran/C functions (because <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">&lt;C-expr&gt;</SPAN></TT> may contain any function =
calls and=20
      F2PY has no way to determine what should be the proper prototype). =
With=20
      this statement you can explicitely specify the arguments of the
       corresponding prototype:</P>
<PRE class=3D"last literal-block">extern &lt;return type&gt; =
FUNC_F(&lt;routine name&gt;,&lt;ROUTINE =
NAME&gt;)(&lt;callprotoargument&gt;);=0A=
</PRE></DD></DL></LI>
    <LI>
    <DL class=3D"first">
      <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">fortranname</SPAN> =
<SPAN class=3D"pre">[&lt;acctual</SPAN>=20
      <SPAN class=3D"pre">Fortran/C</SPAN> <SPAN =
class=3D"pre">routine</SPAN> <SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">name&gt;]</SPAN></TT></DT>
      <DD>
      <P class=3D"first">You can use arbitrary <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">&lt;routine</SPAN>=20
      <SPAN class=3D"pre">name&gt;</SPAN></TT> for a given Fortran/C =
function.=20
      Then you have to specify  <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">&lt;acctual</SPAN> <SPAN =
class=3D"pre">Fortran/C</SPAN> <SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">routine</SPAN> <SPAN =
class=3D"pre">name&gt;</SPAN></TT> with=20
      this statement.</P>
      <P class=3D"last">If <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">fortranname</SPAN></TT> statement is used without =
<TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">&lt;acctual</SPAN> <SPAN =
class=3D"pre">Fortran/C</SPAN> <SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">routine</SPAN> <SPAN =
class=3D"pre">name&gt;</SPAN></TT> then a=20
      dummy wrapper is generated.</P></DD></DL></LI>
    <LI>
    <DL class=3D"first">
      <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">usercode</SPAN> =
<SPAN class=3D"pre">&lt;multi-line</SPAN>=20
      <SPAN class=3D"pre">block&gt;</SPAN></TT></DT>
      <DD>
      <P class=3D"first">When used inside <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">python</SPAN> <SPAN class=3D"pre">module</SPAN></TT> =
block, then=20
      given C code will be inserted to generated C/API source just =
before
       wrapper function definitions. Here you can define arbitrary C =
functions=20
      to be used in initialization of optional arguments, for example. =
If <TT=20
      class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">usercode</SPAN></TT> is used =
twise=20
      inside <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">python</SPAN> =
<SPAN class=3D"pre">module</SPAN></TT>=20
      block then the second multi-line block is inserted after the =
definition of=20
      external routines.</P>
      <P>When used inside <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">&lt;routine</SPAN> <SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">singature&gt;</SPAN></TT>, then given C code will be =
inserted=20
      to the corresponding wrapper function just after declaring =
variables but=20
      before any C statements. So, <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">usercode</SPAN></TT> follow-up can contain both =
declarations=20
      and C statements.</P>
      <P class=3D"last">When used inside the first <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">interface</SPAN></TT> block, then given C code will =
be=20
      inserted at the end of the initialization function of the =
extension=20
      module. Here you can modify extension modules dictionary. For =
example, for=20
      defining additional variables etc.</P></DD></DL></LI>
    <LI>
    <DL class=3D"first">
      <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">pymethoddef</SPAN> =
<SPAN class=3D"pre">&lt;multi-line</SPAN>=20
      <SPAN class=3D"pre">block&gt;</SPAN></TT></DT>
      <DD>
      <P class=3D"first last">Multiline block will be inserted to the =
definition=20
      of module methods <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">PyMethodDef</SPAN></TT>-array. It must be a =
comma-separated=20
      list of C arrays (see <A class=3D"reference" =
href=3D"http://www.python.org/doc/current/ext/ext.html">Extending=20
      and Embedding</A> Python documentation for details). <TT=20
      class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">pymethoddef</SPAN></TT> =
statement can be=20
      used only inside  <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">python</SPAN>=20
      <SPAN class=3D"pre">module</SPAN></TT>=20
block.</P></DD></DL></LI></UL></BLOCKQUOTE></DIV>
<DIV class=3D"section" id=3D"attributes">
<H3><A name=3D"attributes" class=3D"toc-backref" =
href=3D"https://sysbio.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/usersguide/#id27">3.2.3=A0=A0=
=A0Attributes</A></H3>
<P>The following attributes are used by F2PY:</P>
<DL>
  <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">optional</SPAN></TT></DT>
  <DD>
  <P class=3D"first">The corresponding argument is moved to the end of =
<TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">&lt;optional</SPAN> <SPAN =
class=3D"pre">arguments&gt;</SPAN></TT>=20
  list. A default value for an optional argument can be specified <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">&lt;init_expr&gt;</SPAN></TT>, see <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">entitydecl</SPAN></TT> definition. Note that the default =
value=20
  must be given as a valid C expression.</P>
  <P>Note that whenever <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">&lt;init_expr&gt;</SPAN></TT> is used, <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">optional</SPAN></TT> attribute is set automatically by =
F2PY.</P>
  <P class=3D"last">For an optional array argument, all its dimensions =
must be=20
  bounded.</P></DD>
  <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">required</SPAN></TT> =
</DT>
  <DD>
  <P class=3D"first">The corresponding argument is considered as a =
required one.=20
  This is default. You need to specify <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">required</SPAN></TT> only if there is a need to disable =
automatic=20
  <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">optional</SPAN></TT> setting =
when <TT=20
  class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">&lt;init_expr&gt;</SPAN></TT> is =
used.</P>
  <P class=3D"last">If Python <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">None</SPAN></TT> object is used as an required argument, =
the
   argument is treated as optional. That is, in the case of array =
argument, the=20
  memory is allocated. And if <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">&lt;init_expr&gt;</SPAN></TT> is given, the =
corresponding=20
  initialization is carried out.</P></DD>
  <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">dimension(&lt;arrayspec&gt;)</SPAN></TT></DT>
  <DD>The corresponding variable is considered as an array with given =
dimensions=20
  in <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">&lt;arrayspec&gt;</SPAN></TT>.</DD>
  <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">intent(&lt;intentspec&gt;)</SPAN></TT></DT>
  <DD>
  <P class=3D"first">This specifies the "intention" of the corresponding =
argument.=20
  <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">&lt;intentspec&gt;</SPAN></TT> is a=20
  comma separated list of the following keys:</P>
  <UL>
    <LI>
    <DL class=3D"first">
      <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">in</SPAN></TT></DT>
      <DD>
      <P class=3D"first last">The argument is considered as an =
input-only=20
      argument. It means that the value of the argument is passed to =
Fortran/C=20
      function and that function is expected not to change the value of =
an=20
      argument.</P></DD></DL></LI>
    <LI>
    <DL class=3D"first">
      <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">inout</SPAN></TT></DT>
      <DD>
      <P class=3D"first">The argument is considered as an input/output =
or <EM>in=20
      situ</EM> output argument. <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">intent(inout)</SPAN></TT> arguments can be only =
"contiguous"=20
      Numeric arrays with proper type and size.  Here "contiguous" can =
be either=20
      in Fortran or C sense. The latter one coincides with the =
contiguous=20
      concept used in Numeric and is effective only if <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">intent(c)</SPAN></TT> is used. =
Fortran-contiguousness is=20
      assumed by default.</P>
      <P class=3D"last">Using <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">intent(inout)</SPAN></TT> is generally not =
recommended, use=20
      <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">intent(in,out)</SPAN></TT> instead.=20
      See also <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">intent(inplace)</SPAN></TT>=20
      attribute.</P></DD></DL></LI>
    <LI>
    <DL class=3D"first">
      <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">inplace</SPAN></TT></DT>
      <DD>
      <P class=3D"first">The argument is considered as an input/output =
or <EM>in=20
      situ</EM> output argument. <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">intent(inplace)</SPAN></TT> arguments must be =
Numeric arrays=20
      with proper size. If the type of an array is not "proper" or the =
array is=20
      non-contiguous then the array will be changed in-place to fix the =
type and=20
      make it contiguous.</P>
      <P class=3D"last">Using <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">intent(inplace)</SPAN></TT> is generally not =
recommended=20
      either. For example, when slices have been taken from an <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">intent(inplace)</SPAN></TT> argument then after =
in-place=20
      changes, slices data pointers may point to unallocated memory=20
      area.</P></DD></DL></LI>
    <LI>
    <DL class=3D"first">
      <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">out</SPAN></TT></DT>
      <DD>
      <P class=3D"first">The argument is considered as an return =
variable. It is=20
      appended to the <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">&lt;returned</SPAN>=20
      <SPAN class=3D"pre">variables&gt;</SPAN></TT> list. Using <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">intent(out)</SPAN></TT> sets <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">intent(hide)</SPAN></TT>=20
      automatically, unless also <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">intent(in)</SPAN></TT> or <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">intent(inout)</SPAN></TT>=20
      were used.</P>
      <P class=3D"last">By default, returned multidimensional arrays are
       Fortran-contiguous. If <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">intent(c)</SPAN></TT> is used, then returned =
multi-dimensional=20
      arrays are C-contiguous.</P></DD></DL></LI>
    <LI>
    <DL class=3D"first">
      <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">hide</SPAN></TT></DT>
      <DD>
      <P class=3D"first">The argument is removed from the list of =
required or=20
      optional arguments. Typically <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">intent(hide)</SPAN></TT> is used with <TT=20
      class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">intent(out)</SPAN></TT> or =
when <TT=20
      class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">&lt;init_expr&gt;</SPAN></TT> completely=20
      determines the value of the argument like in the following =
example:</P>
<PRE class=3D"last literal-block">integer intent(hide),depend(a) :: n =
=3D len(a)=0A=
real intent(in),dimension(n) :: a      =0A=
</PRE></DD></DL></LI>
    <LI>
    <DL class=3D"first">
      <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">c</SPAN></TT></DT>
      <DD>
      <P class=3D"first">The argument is treated as a C scalar or C =
array=20
      argument.  In the case of a scalar argument, its value is passed =
to C=20
      function as a C scalar argument (recall that Fortran scalar =
arguments are
       actually C pointer arguments).  In the case of an array argument, =
the=20
      wrapper function is assumed to treat multi-dimensional arrays as=20
      C-contiguous arrays.</P>
      <P>There is no need to use <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">intent(c)</SPAN></TT> for one-dimensional arrays, no =
matter if=20
      the wrapped function is either a Fortran or a C function. This is =
because=20
      the concepts of Fortran- and C-contiguousness overlap in =
one-dimensional=20
      cases.</P>
      <P>If <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">intent(c)</SPAN></TT> is used=20
      as an statement but without entity declaration list, then F2PY =
adds <TT=20
      class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">intent(c)</SPAN></TT> =
attibute to all
       arguments.</P>
      <P class=3D"last">Also, when wrapping C functions, one must use =
<TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">intent(c)</SPAN></TT> attribute for <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">&lt;routine</SPAN> <SPAN =
class=3D"pre">name&gt;</SPAN></TT> in=20
      order to disable Fortran specific <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">F_FUNC(..,..)</SPAN></TT> macros.</P></DD></DL></LI>
    <LI>
    <DL class=3D"first">
      <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">cache</SPAN></TT></DT>
      <DD>
      <P class=3D"first last">The argument is treated as a junk of =
memory. No=20
      Fortran nor C contiguousness checks are carried out. Using <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">intent(cache)</SPAN></TT> makes sense only for array =

      arguments, also in connection with <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">intent(hide)</SPAN></TT> or <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">optional</SPAN></TT>=20
      attributes.</P></DD></DL></LI>
    <LI>
    <DL class=3D"first">
      <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">copy</SPAN></TT></DT>
      <DD>
      <P class=3D"first last">Ensure that the original contents of <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">intent(in)</SPAN></TT> argument is preserved. =
Typically used=20
      in connection with <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">intent(in,out)</SPAN></TT> attribute.  F2PY creates =
an=20
      optional argument <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">overwrite_&lt;argument</SPAN> <SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">name&gt;</SPAN></TT> with the default value <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">0</SPAN></TT>.</P></DD></DL></LI>
    <LI>
    <DL class=3D"first">
      <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">overwrite</SPAN></TT></DT>
      <DD>
      <P class=3D"first last">The original contents of the <TT=20
      class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">intent(in)</SPAN></TT> =
argument may be
       altered by the Fortran/C function.  F2PY creates an optional =
argument <TT=20
      class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">overwrite_&lt;argument</SPAN> <SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">name&gt;</SPAN></TT> with the default value <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">1</SPAN></TT>.</P></DD></DL></LI>
    <LI>
    <DL class=3D"first">
      <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">out=3D&lt;new</SPAN> =
<SPAN class=3D"pre">name&gt;</SPAN></TT></DT>
      <DD>
      <P class=3D"first last">Replace the return name with <TT=20
      class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">&lt;new</SPAN> <SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">name&gt;</SPAN></TT> in the <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">__doc__</SPAN></TT>
       string of a wrapper function.</P></DD></DL></LI>
    <LI>
    <DL class=3D"first">
      <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">callback</SPAN></TT></DT>
      <DD>
      <P class=3D"first">Construct an external function suitable for =
calling=20
      Python function from Fortran. <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">intent(callback)</SPAN></TT> must be specified =
before the
       corresponding <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">external</SPAN></TT>=20
      statement. If 'argument' is not in argument list then it will be =
added to=20
      Python wrapper but is not used when calling Fortran function.</P>
      <P class=3D"last">Use <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
      class=3D"pre">intent(callback)</SPAN></TT> in situations where a =
Fortran/C=20
      code assumes that a user implements a function with given =
prototype and=20
      links it to an executable.</P></DD></DL></LI>
    <LI>
    <DL class=3D"first">
      <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">aux</SPAN></TT></DT>
      <DD>
      <P class=3D"first last">Define auxiliary C variable in F2PY =
generated=20
      wrapper function. Useful to save parameter values so that they can =
be=20
      accessed in initialization expression of other variables. Note =
that <TT=20
      class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">intent(aux)</SPAN></TT> =
silently implies=20
      <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
    class=3D"pre">intent(c)</SPAN></TT>.</P></DD></DL></LI></UL>
  <P>The following rules apply:</P>
  <UL class=3D"last simple">
    <LI>If no <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">intent(in</SPAN> =
<SPAN=20
    class=3D"pre">|</SPAN> <SPAN class=3D"pre">inout</SPAN> <SPAN=20
    class=3D"pre">|</SPAN> <SPAN class=3D"pre">out</SPAN> <SPAN =
class=3D"pre">|</SPAN>=20
    <SPAN class=3D"pre">hide)</SPAN></TT> is specified, <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
    class=3D"pre">intent(in)</SPAN></TT> is assumed.</LI>
    <LI><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">intent(in,inout)</SPAN></TT> is=20
    <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">intent(in)</SPAN></TT>.</LI>
    <LI><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">intent(in,hide)</SPAN></TT> or <TT=20
    class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">intent(inout,hide)</SPAN></TT> =
is <TT=20
    class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">intent(hide)</SPAN></TT>.</LI>
    <LI><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">intent(out)</SPAN></TT> is <TT=20
    class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">intent(out,hide)</SPAN></TT> =
unless <TT=20
    class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">intent(in)</SPAN></TT> or <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
    class=3D"pre">intent(inout)</SPAN></TT> is specified.</LI>
    <LI>If <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">intent(copy)</SPAN></TT> or <TT=20
    class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">intent(overwrite)</SPAN></TT> =
is used,=20
    then an additional optional argument is introduced with a name <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
    class=3D"pre">overwrite_&lt;argument</SPAN> <SPAN=20
    class=3D"pre">name&gt;</SPAN></TT> and a default value 0 or 1,=20
    respectively.</LI>
    <LI><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">intent(inout,inplace)</SPAN></TT>=20
    is <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">intent(inplace)</SPAN></TT>.</LI>
    <LI><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">intent(in,inplace)</SPAN></TT> is=20
    <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">intent(inplace)</SPAN></TT>.</LI></UL></DD>
  <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">check([&lt;C-booleanexpr&gt;])</SPAN></TT></DT>
  <DD>
  <P class=3D"first">Perform consistency check of arguments by =
evaluating <TT=20
  class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">&lt;C-booleanexpr&gt;</SPAN></TT>; if <TT=20
  class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">&lt;C-booleanexpr&gt;</SPAN></TT> returns 0,=20
  an exception is raised.</P>
  <P class=3D"last">If <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">check(..)</SPAN></TT>=20
  is not used then F2PY generates few standard checks (e.g. in a case of =
an=20
  array argument, check for the proper shape and size) automatically. =
Use <TT=20
  class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">check()</SPAN></TT> to disable =
checks=20
  generated by F2PY.</P></DD>
  <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">depend([&lt;names&gt;])</SPAN></TT></DT>
  <DD>
  <P class=3D"first">This declares that the corresponding argument =
depends on the=20
  values of variables in the list <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">&lt;names&gt;</SPAN></TT>. For example, <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">&lt;init_expr&gt;</SPAN></TT> may use the values of =
other=20
  arguments.  Using information given by <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">depend(..)</SPAN></TT> attributes, F2PY ensures that =
arguments are
   initialized in a proper order. If <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">depend(..)</SPAN></TT> attribute is not used then F2PY =
determines=20
  dependence relations automatically. Use <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">depend()</SPAN></TT> to disable dependence relations =
generated by=20
  F2PY.</P>
  <P class=3D"last">When you edit dependence relations that were =
initially=20
  generated by F2PY, be careful not to break the dependence relations of =
other
   relevant variables. Another thing to watch out is cyclic =
dependencies. F2PY=20
  is able to detect cyclic dependencies when constructing wrappers and =
it=20
  complains if any are found.</P></DD>
  <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">allocatable</SPAN></TT></DT>
  <DD>The corresponding variable is Fortran 90 allocatable array defined =
as=20
  Fortran 90 module data.</DD></DL><A name=3D"external" class=3D"target" =

id=3D"external"></A>
<DL>=20
  <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">external</SPAN></TT></DT>
  <DD>
  <P class=3D"first">The corresponding argument is a function provided =
by user.=20
  The signature of this so-called call-back function can be defined</P>
  <UL class=3D"simple">
    <LI>in <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">__user__</SPAN></TT> module=20
    block,</LI>
    <LI>or by demonstrative (or real, if the signature file is a real =
Fortran
     code) call in the <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">&lt;other</SPAN>=20
    <SPAN class=3D"pre">statements&gt;</SPAN></TT> block.</LI></UL>
  <P>For example, F2PY generates from</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">external cb_sub, cb_fun=0A=
integer n=0A=
real a(n),r=0A=
call cb_sub(a,n)=0A=
r =3D cb_fun(4)=0A=
</PRE>
  <P>the following call-back signatures:</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">subroutine cb_sub(a,n)=0A=
    real dimension(n) :: a=0A=
    integer optional,check(len(a)&gt;=3Dn),depend(a) :: n=3Dlen(a)=0A=
end subroutine cb_sub=0A=
function cb_fun(e_4_e) result (r)=0A=
    integer :: e_4_e=0A=
    real :: r=0A=
end function cb_fun=0A=
</PRE>
  <P>The corresponding user-provided Python function are then:</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">def cb_sub(a,[n]):=0A=
    ...=0A=
    return=0A=
def cb_fun(e_4_e):=0A=
    ...=0A=
    return r=0A=
</PRE>
  <P class=3D"last">See also <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">intent(callback)</SPAN></TT> attribute.</P></DD>
  <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">parameter</SPAN></TT></DT>
  <DD>The corresponding variable is a parameter and it must have a fixed =
value.=20
  F2PY replaces all parameter occurrences by their corresponding=20
values.</DD></DL></DIV></DIV>
<DIV class=3D"section" id=3D"extensions">
<H2><A name=3D"extensions" class=3D"toc-backref" =
href=3D"https://sysbio.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/usersguide/#id28">3.3=A0=A0=
=A0Extensions</A></H2>
<DIV class=3D"section" id=3D"f2py-directives">
<H3><A name=3D"f2py-directives" class=3D"toc-backref" =
href=3D"https://sysbio.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/usersguide/#id29">3.3.1=A0=A0=
=A0F2PY=20
directives</A></H3>
<P>The so-called F2PY directives allow using F2PY signature file =
constructs also=20
in Fortran 77/90 source codes. With this feature you can skip (almost)=20
completely intermediate signature file generations and apply F2PY =
directly to=20
Fortran source codes.</P>
<P>F2PY directive has the following form:</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">&lt;comment char&gt;f2py ...=0A=
</PRE>
<P>where allowed comment characters for fixed and free format Fortran =
codes are=20
<TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">cC*!#</SPAN></TT> and <TT=20
class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">!</SPAN></TT>, respectively. =
Everything that=20
follows <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">&lt;comment</SPAN> =
<SPAN class=3D"pre">char&gt;f2py</SPAN></TT>=20
is ignored by a compiler but read by F2PY as a normal Fortran =
(non-comment)=20
line:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>When F2PY finds a line with F2PY directive, the directive is =
first
   replaced by 5 spaces and then the line is reread.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>For fixed format Fortran codes, <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">&lt;comment</SPAN> <SPAN =
class=3D"pre">char&gt;</SPAN></TT> must be at=20
the first column of a file, of course. For free format Fortran codes, =
F2PY=20
directives can appear anywhere in a file.</P></DIV>
<DIV class=3D"section" id=3D"c-expressions">
<H3><A name=3D"c-expressions" class=3D"toc-backref" =
href=3D"https://sysbio.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/usersguide/#id30">3.3.2=A0=A0=
=A0C=20
expressions</A></H3>
<P>C expressions are used in the following parts of signature files:</P>
<UL class=3D"simple">
  <LI><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">&lt;init_expr&gt;</SPAN></TT> of=20
  variable initialization;</LI>
  <LI><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">&lt;C-booleanexpr&gt;</SPAN></TT> of=20
  the <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">check</SPAN></TT> =
attribute;</LI>
  <LI><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">&lt;arrayspec&gt;</SPAN> =
<SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">of</SPAN> <SPAN class=3D"pre">the</SPAN> <SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">``dimension</SPAN></TT> attribute;</LI>
  <LI><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">callstatement</SPAN></TT> statement,=20
  here also a C multi-line block can be used.</LI></UL>
<P>A C expression may contain:</P>
<UL>
  <LI>
  <P class=3D"first">standard C constructs;</P></LI>
  <LI>
  <P class=3D"first">functions from <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">math.h</SPAN></TT> and <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">Python.h</SPAN></TT>;</P></LI>
  <LI>
  <P class=3D"first">variables from the argument list, presumably =
initialized=20
  before according to given dependence relations;</P></LI>
  <LI>
  <P class=3D"first">the following CPP macros:</P>
  <DL>
    <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">rank(&lt;name&gt;)</SPAN></TT></DT>
    <DD>
    <P class=3D"first last">Returns the rank of an array <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
    class=3D"pre">&lt;name&gt;</SPAN></TT>.</P></DD>
    <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
    class=3D"pre">shape(&lt;name&gt;,&lt;n&gt;)</SPAN></TT></DT>
    <DD>
    <P class=3D"first last">Returns the <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
    class=3D"pre">&lt;n&gt;</SPAN></TT>-th dimension of an array <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
    class=3D"pre">&lt;name&gt;</SPAN></TT>.</P></DD>
    <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">len(&lt;name&gt;)</SPAN></TT></DT>
    <DD>
    <P class=3D"first last">Returns the lenght of an array <TT=20
    class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">&lt;name&gt;</SPAN></TT>.</P></DD>
    <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">size(&lt;name&gt;)</SPAN></TT></DT>
    <DD>
    <P class=3D"first last">Returns the size of an array <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
    class=3D"pre">&lt;name&gt;</SPAN></TT>.</P></DD>
    <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">slen(&lt;name&gt;)</SPAN></TT></DT>
    <DD>
    <P class=3D"first last">Returns the length of a string <TT=20
    class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">&lt;name&gt;</SPAN></TT>.</P></DD></DL></LI></UL>
<P>For initializing an array <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">&lt;array</SPAN> <SPAN class=3D"pre">name&gt;</SPAN></TT>, =
F2PY=20
generates a loop over all indices and dimensions that executes the =
following
 pseudo-statement:</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">&lt;array name&gt;(_i[0],_i[1],...) =3D =
&lt;init_expr&gt;;=0A=
</PRE>
<P>where <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">_i[&lt;i&gt;]</SPAN></TT> refers=20
to the <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">&lt;i&gt;</SPAN></TT>-th index=20
value and that runs from <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">0</SPAN></TT> to=20
<TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">shape(&lt;array</SPAN> <SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">name&gt;,&lt;i&gt;)-1</SPAN></TT>.</P>
<P>For example, a function <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">myrange(n)</SPAN></TT> generated from the following =
signature</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">subroutine myrange(a,n)=0A=
  fortranname        ! myrange is a dummy wrapper=0A=
  integer intent(in) :: n=0A=
  real*8 intent(c,out),dimension(n),depend(n) :: a =3D _i[0]=0A=
end subroutine myrange=0A=
</PRE>
<P>is equivalent to <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">Numeric.arange(n,typecode=3D'd')</SPAN></TT>.</P>
<DIV class=3D"topic">
<P class=3D"topic-title">Warning!</P>
<P>F2PY may lower cases also in C expressions when scanning Fortran =
codes (see=20
<TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">--[no]-lower</SPAN></TT>=20
option).</P></DIV></DIV>
<DIV class=3D"section" id=3D"multi-line-blocks">
<H3><A name=3D"multi-line-blocks" class=3D"toc-backref" =
href=3D"https://sysbio.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/usersguide/#id31">3.3.3=A0=A0=
=A0Multi-line=20
blocks</A></H3>
<P>A multi-line block starts with <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">'''</SPAN></TT> (triple single-quotes) and ends with <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">'''</SPAN></TT> in some <EM>strictly</EM> subsequent line. =
=20
Multi-line blocks can be used only within .pyf files. The contents of a=20
multi-line block can be arbitrary (except that it cannot contain <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">'''</SPAN></TT>) and no transformations (e.g. lowering =
cases) are=20
applied to it.</P>
<P>Currently, multi-line blocks can be used in the following =
constructs:</P>
<UL class=3D"simple">
  <LI>as a C expression of the <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">callstatement</SPAN></TT> statement;</LI>
  <LI>as a C type specification of the <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">callprotoargument</SPAN></TT> statement;</LI>
  <LI>as a C code block of the <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">usercode</SPAN></TT> statement;</LI>
  <LI>as a list of C arrays of the <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">pymethoddef</SPAN></TT> statement;</LI>
  <LI>as documentation string.</LI></UL></DIV></DIV></DIV>
<DIV class=3D"section" id=3D"using-f2py-bindings-in-python">
<H1><A name=3D"using-f2py-bindings-in-python" class=3D"toc-backref" =
href=3D"https://sysbio.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/usersguide/#id32">4=A0=A0=A0=
Using=20
F2PY bindings in Python</A></H1>
<P>All wrappers (to Fortran/C routines or to common blocks or to Fortran =
90=20
module data) generated by F2PY are exposed to Python as <TT=20
class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">fortran</SPAN></TT> type objects.  =
Routine=20
wrappers are callable <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">fortran</SPAN></TT>=20
type objects while wrappers to Fortran data have attributes referring to =
data
 objects.</P>
<P>All <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">fortran</SPAN></TT> =
type object=20
have attribute <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">_cpointer</SPAN></TT> that=20
contains CObject referring to the C pointer of the corresponding =
Fortran/C
 function or variable in C level. Such CObjects can be used as an =
callback=20
argument of F2PY generated functions to bypass Python C/API  layer of =
calling=20
Python functions from Fortran or C when the computational part of such =
functions=20
is implemented in C or Fortran and wrapped with F2PY (or any other tool =
capable=20
of providing CObject of a function).</P>
<DIV class=3D"topic">
<P class=3D"topic-title">Example</P>
<P>Consider a <A class=3D"reference" =
href=3D"https://sysbio.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/usersguide/ftype.f">Fortran=
=20
77 file</A> <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">ftype.f</SPAN></TT>:</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">C FILE: FTYPE.F=0A=
      SUBROUTINE FOO(N)=0A=
      INTEGER N=0A=
Cf2py integer optional,intent(in) :: n =3D 13=0A=
      REAL A,X=0A=
      COMMON /DATA/ A,X(3)=0A=
      PRINT*, "IN FOO: N=3D",N," A=3D",A," X=3D[",X(1),X(2),X(3),"]"=0A=
      END=0A=
C END OF FTYPE.F=0A=
=0A=
</PRE>
<P>and build a wrapper using:</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">f2py -c ftype.f -m ftype=0A=
</PRE>
<P>In Python:</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">&gt;&gt;&gt; import ftype=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; print ftype.__doc__=0A=
This module 'ftype' is auto-generated with f2py (version:2.28.198-1366).=0A=
Functions:=0A=
  foo(n=3D13)=0A=
COMMON blocks:=0A=
  /data/ a,x(3)=0A=
.=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; type(ftype.foo),type(ftype.data)=0A=
(&lt;type 'fortran'&gt;, &lt;type 'fortran'&gt;)=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; ftype.foo()=0A=
 IN FOO: N=3D 13 A=3D  0. X=3D[  0.  0.  0.]=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; ftype.data.a =3D 3=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; ftype.data.x =3D [1,2,3]=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; ftype.foo()=0A=
 IN FOO: N=3D 13 A=3D  3. X=3D[  1.  2.  3.]=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; ftype.data.x[1] =3D 45  =0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; ftype.foo(24)=0A=
 IN FOO: N=3D 24 A=3D  3. X=3D[  1.  45.  3.]=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; ftype.data.x=0A=
array([  1.,  45.,   3.],'f')=0A=
=0A=
</PRE></DIV>
<DIV class=3D"section" id=3D"scalar-arguments">
<H2><A name=3D"scalar-arguments" class=3D"toc-backref" =
href=3D"https://sysbio.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/usersguide/#id33">4.1=A0=A0=
=A0Scalar=20
arguments</A></H2>
<P>In general, a scalar argument of a F2PY generated wrapper function =
can be=20
ordinary Python scalar (integer, float, complex number) as well as an =
arbitrary=20
sequence object (list, tuple, array, string) of scalars. In the latter =
case, the=20
first element of the sequence object is passed to Fortran routine as a =
scalar=20
argument.</P>
<P>Note that when type-casting is required and there is possible loss of
 information (e.g. when type-casting float to integer or complex to =
float), F2PY=20
does not raise any exception. In complex to real type-casting only the =
real part=20
of a complex number is used.</P>
<P><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">intent(inout)</SPAN></TT> =
scalar=20
arguments are assumed to be array objects in order to <EM>in situ</EM> =
changes=20
to be effective. It is recommended to use arrays with proper type but =
also other=20
types work.</P>
<DIV class=3D"topic">
<P class=3D"topic-title">Example</P>
<P>Consider the following <A class=3D"reference" =
href=3D"https://sysbio.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/usersguide/scalar.f">Fortra=
n=20
77 code</A>:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">C FILE: SCALAR.F=0A=
      SUBROUTINE FOO(A,B)=0A=
      REAL*8 A, B=0A=
Cf2py intent(in) a=0A=
Cf2py intent(inout) b=0A=
      PRINT*, "    A=3D",A," B=3D",B=0A=
      PRINT*, "INCREMENT A AND B"=0A=
      A =3D A + 1D0=0A=
      B =3D B + 1D0=0A=
      PRINT*, "NEW A=3D",A," B=3D",B=0A=
      END=0A=
C END OF FILE SCALAR.F=0A=
=0A=
</PRE></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>and wrap it using <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">f2py</SPAN> <SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">-c</SPAN> <SPAN class=3D"pre">-m</SPAN> <SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">scalar</SPAN> <SPAN =
class=3D"pre">scalar.f</SPAN></TT>.</P>
<P>In Python:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">&gt;&gt;&gt; import scalar=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; print scalar.foo.__doc__=0A=
foo - Function signature:=0A=
  foo(a,b)=0A=
Required arguments:=0A=
  a : input float=0A=
  b : in/output rank-0 array(float,'d')=0A=
 =0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; scalar.foo(2,3)   =0A=
     A=3D  2. B=3D  3.=0A=
 INCREMENT A AND B=0A=
 NEW A=3D  3. B=3D  4.=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; import Numeric=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; a=3DNumeric.array(2)   # these are integer rank-0 arrays=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; b=3DNumeric.array(3)=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; scalar.foo(a,b)=0A=
     A=3D  2. B=3D  3.=0A=
 INCREMENT A AND B=0A=
 NEW A=3D  3. B=3D  4.=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; print a,b            # note that only b is changed in situ=0A=
2 4=0A=
</PRE></BLOCKQUOTE></DIV></DIV>
<DIV class=3D"section" id=3D"string-arguments">
<H2><A name=3D"string-arguments" class=3D"toc-backref" =
href=3D"https://sysbio.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/usersguide/#id34">4.2=A0=A0=
=A0String=20
arguments</A></H2>
<P>F2PY generated wrapper functions accept (almost) any Python object as =
a=20
string argument, <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">str</SPAN></TT> is=20
applied for non-string objects. Exceptions are Numeric arrays that must =
have=20
type code <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">'c'</SPAN></TT> or =
<TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">'1'</SPAN></TT> when used as string arguments.</P>
<P>A string can have arbitrary length when using it as a string argument =
to F2PY=20
generated wrapper function. If the length is greater than expected, the =
string=20
is truncated. If the length is smaller that expected, additional memory =
is=20
allocated and filled with <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">\0</SPAN></TT>.</P>
<P>Because Python strings are immutable, an <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">intent(inout)</SPAN></TT>=20
argument expects an array version of a string in order to <EM>in =
situ</EM>=20
changes to be effective.</P>
<DIV class=3D"topic">
<P class=3D"topic-title">Example</P>
<P>Consider the following <A class=3D"reference" =
href=3D"https://sysbio.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/usersguide/string.f">Fortra=
n=20
77 code</A>:</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">C FILE: STRING.F=0A=
      SUBROUTINE FOO(A,B,C,D)=0A=
      CHARACTER*5 A, B=0A=
      CHARACTER*(*) C,D=0A=
Cf2py intent(in) a,c=0A=
Cf2py intent(inout) b,d=0A=
      PRINT*, "A=3D",A=0A=
      PRINT*, "B=3D",B=0A=
      PRINT*, "C=3D",C=0A=
      PRINT*, "D=3D",D=0A=
      PRINT*, "CHANGE A,B,C,D"=0A=
      A(1:1) =3D 'A'=0A=
      B(1:1) =3D 'B'=0A=
      C(1:1) =3D 'C'=0A=
      D(1:1) =3D 'D'=0A=
      PRINT*, "A=3D",A=0A=
      PRINT*, "B=3D",B=0A=
      PRINT*, "C=3D",C=0A=
      PRINT*, "D=3D",D=0A=
      END=0A=
C END OF FILE STRING.F=0A=
=0A=
</PRE>
<P>and wrap it using <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">f2py</SPAN> <SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">-c</SPAN> <SPAN class=3D"pre">-m</SPAN> <SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">mystring</SPAN> <SPAN =
class=3D"pre">string.f</SPAN></TT>.</P>
<P>Python session:</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">&gt;&gt;&gt; import mystring=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; print mystring.foo.__doc__=0A=
foo - Function signature:=0A=
  foo(a,b,c,d)=0A=
Required arguments:=0A=
  a : input string(len=3D5)=0A=
  b : in/output rank-0 array(string(len=3D5),'c')=0A=
  c : input string(len=3D-1)=0A=
  d : in/output rank-0 array(string(len=3D-1),'c')=0A=
=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; import Numeric=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; a=3DNumeric.array('123')=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; b=3DNumeric.array('123')=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; c=3DNumeric.array('123')=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; d=3DNumeric.array('123')=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; mystring.foo(a,b,c,d)=0A=
 A=3D123=0A=
 B=3D123=0A=
 C=3D123=0A=
 D=3D123=0A=
 CHANGE A,B,C,D=0A=
 A=3DA23=0A=
 B=3DB23=0A=
 C=3DC23=0A=
 D=3DD23=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; a.tostring(),b.tostring(),c.tostring(),d.tostring()=0A=
('123', 'B23', '123', 'D23')=0A=
</PRE></DIV></DIV>
<DIV class=3D"section" id=3D"array-arguments">
<H2><A name=3D"array-arguments" class=3D"toc-backref" =
href=3D"https://sysbio.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/usersguide/#id35">4.3=A0=A0=
=A0Array=20
arguments</A></H2>
<P>In general, array arguments of F2PY generated wrapper functions =
accept
 arbitrary sequences that can be transformed to Numeric array objects. =
An=20
exception is <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">intent(inout)</SPAN></TT>=20
array arguments that always must be proper-contiguous and have proper =
type,=20
otherwise an exception is raised. Another exception is <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">intent(inplace)</SPAN></TT> array arguments that =
attributes will be=20
changed in-situ if the argument has different type than expected (see =
<TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">intent(inplace)</SPAN></TT> attribute for more =
information).</P>
<P>In general, if a Numeric array is proper-contiguous and has a proper =
type=20
then it is directly passed to wrapped Fortran/C function. Otherwise, an=20
element-wise copy of an input array is made and the copy, being=20
proper-contiguous and with proper type, is used as an array =
argument.</P>
<P>There are two types of proper-contiguous Numeric arrays:</P>
<UL class=3D"simple">
  <LI>Fortran-contiguous arrays when data is stored column-wise, i.e. =
indexing=20
  of data as stored in memory starts from the lowest dimension;</LI>
  <LI>C-contiguous or simply contiguous arrays when data is stored =
row-wise,=20
  i.e. indexing of data as stored in memory starts from the highest=20
  dimension.</LI></UL>
<P>For one-dimensional arrays these notions coincide.</P>
<P>For example, an 2x2 array <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">A</SPAN></TT>=20
is Fortran-contiguous if its elements are stored in memory in the =
following=20
order:</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">A[0,0] A[1,0] A[0,1] A[1,1]=0A=
</PRE>
<P>and C-contiguous if the order is as follows:</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">A[0,0] A[0,1] A[1,0] A[1,1]=0A=
</PRE>
<P>To test whether an array is C-contiguous, use <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">.iscontiguous()</SPAN></TT> method of Numeric arrays.  To =
test for=20
Fortran-contiguousness, all F2PY generated extension modules provide a =
function=20
<TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">has_column_major_storage(&lt;array&gt;)</SPAN></TT>. This =
function=20
is equivalent to <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">Numeric.transpose(&lt;array&gt;).iscontiguous()</SPAN></TT>=
 but more=20
efficient.</P>
<P>Usually there is no need to worry about how the arrays are stored in =
memory=20
and whether the wrapped functions, being either Fortran or C functions, =
assume=20
one or another storage order. F2PY automatically ensures that wrapped =
functions=20
get arguments with proper storage order; the corresponding algorithm is =
designed=20
to make copies of arrays only when absolutely necessary. However, when =
dealing=20
with very large multi-dimensional input arrays with sizes close to the =
size of
 the physical memory in your computer, then a care must be taken to use =
always=20
proper-contiguous and proper type arguments.</P>
<P>To transform input arrays to column major storage order before =
passing them=20
to Fortran routines, use a function <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">as_column_major_storage(&lt;array&gt;)</SPAN></TT> that is =
provided=20
by all F2PY generated extension modules.</P>
<DIV class=3D"topic">
<P class=3D"topic-title">Example</P>
<P>Consider <A class=3D"reference" =
href=3D"https://sysbio.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/usersguide/array.f">Fortran=
=20
77 code</A>:</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">C FILE: ARRAY.F=0A=
      SUBROUTINE FOO(A,N,M)=0A=
C=0A=
C     INCREMENT THE FIRST ROW AND DECREMENT THE FIRST COLUMN OF A=0A=
C=0A=
      INTEGER N,M,I,J=0A=
      REAL*8 A(N,M)=0A=
Cf2py intent(in,out,copy) a=0A=
Cf2py integer intent(hide),depend(a) :: n=3Dshape(a,0), m=3Dshape(a,1)=0A=
      DO J=3D1,M=0A=
         A(1,J) =3D A(1,J) + 1D0=0A=
      ENDDO=0A=
      DO I=3D1,N=0A=
         A(I,1) =3D A(I,1) - 1D0=0A=
      ENDDO=0A=
      END=0A=
C END OF FILE ARRAY.F=0A=
=0A=
</PRE>
<P>and wrap it using <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">f2py</SPAN> <SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">-c</SPAN> <SPAN class=3D"pre">-m</SPAN> <SPAN =
class=3D"pre">arr</SPAN>=20
<SPAN class=3D"pre">array.f</SPAN> <SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">-DF2PY_REPORT_ON_ARRAY_COPY=3D1</SPAN></TT>.</P>
<P>In Python:</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">&gt;&gt;&gt; import arr=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; from Numeric import array=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; print arr.foo.__doc__=0A=
foo - Function signature:=0A=
  a =3D foo(a,[overwrite_a])=0A=
Required arguments:=0A=
  a : input rank-2 array('d') with bounds (n,m)=0A=
Optional arguments:=0A=
  overwrite_a :=3D 0 input int=0A=
Return objects:=0A=
  a : rank-2 array('d') with bounds (n,m)=0A=
=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; a=3Darr.foo([[1,2,3],=0A=
...            [4,5,6]])=0A=
copied an array using PyArray_CopyFromObject: size=3D6, elsize=3D8=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; print a=0A=
[[ 1.  3.  4.]=0A=
 [ 3.  5.  6.]]=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; a.iscontiguous(), arr.has_column_major_storage(a)=0A=
(0, 1)=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; b=3Darr.foo(a)              # even if a is proper-contiguous=0A=
...                           # and has proper type, a copy is made=0A=
...                           # forced by intent(copy) attribute=0A=
...                           # to preserve its original contents=0A=
... =0A=
copied an array using copy_ND_array: size=3D6, elsize=3D8=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; print a=0A=
[[ 1.  3.  4.]=0A=
 [ 3.  5.  6.]]=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; print b=0A=
[[ 1.  4.  5.]=0A=
 [ 2.  5.  6.]]=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; b=3Darr.foo(a,overwrite_a=3D1) # a is passed directly to =
Fortran=0A=
...                            # routine and its contents is discarded=0A=
... =0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; print a=0A=
[[ 1.  4.  5.]=0A=
 [ 2.  5.  6.]]=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; print b=0A=
[[ 1.  4.  5.]=0A=
 [ 2.  5.  6.]]=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; a is b                       # a and b are acctually the =
same objects=0A=
1=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; print arr.foo([1,2,3])       # different rank arrays are =
allowed=0A=
copied an array using PyArray_CopyFromObject: size=3D3, elsize=3D8=0A=
[ 1.  1.  2.]=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; print arr.foo([[[1],[2],[3]]])=0A=
copied an array using PyArray_CopyFromObject: size=3D3, elsize=3D8=0A=
[ [[ 1.]=0A=
  [ 3.]=0A=
  [ 4.]]]=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt;=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; # Creating arrays with column major data storage order:=0A=
...=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; s =3D arr.as_column_major_storage(array([[1,2,3],[4,5,6]]))=0A=
copied an array using copy_ND_array: size=3D6, elsize=3D4=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; arr.has_column_major_storage(s)=0A=
1=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; print s=0A=
[[1 2 3]=0A=
 [4 5 6]]=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; s2 =3D arr.as_column_major_storage(s)=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; s2 is s    # an array with column major storage order =0A=
               # is returned immediately=0A=
1=0A=
</PRE></DIV></DIV>
<DIV class=3D"section" id=3D"call-back-arguments">
<H2><A name=3D"call-back-arguments" class=3D"toc-backref" =
href=3D"https://sysbio.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/usersguide/#id36">4.4=A0=A0=
=A0Call-back=20
arguments</A></H2>
<P>F2PY supports calling Python functions from Fortran or C codes.</P>
<DIV class=3D"topic">
<P class=3D"topic-title">Example</P>
<P>Consider the following <A class=3D"reference" =
href=3D"https://sysbio.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/usersguide/callback.f">Fort=
ran=20
77 code</A></P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">C FILE: CALLBACK.F=0A=
      SUBROUTINE FOO(FUN,R)=0A=
      EXTERNAL FUN=0A=
      INTEGER I=0A=
      REAL*8 R=0A=
Cf2py intent(out) r=0A=
      R =3D 0D0=0A=
      DO I=3D-5,5=0A=
         R =3D R + FUN(I)=0A=
      ENDDO=0A=
      END=0A=
C END OF FILE CALLBACK.F=0A=
=0A=
</PRE>
<P>and wrap it using <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">f2py</SPAN> <SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">-c</SPAN> <SPAN class=3D"pre">-m</SPAN> <SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">callback</SPAN> <SPAN =
class=3D"pre">callback.f</SPAN></TT>.</P>
<P>In Python:</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">&gt;&gt;&gt; import callback=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; print callback.foo.__doc__=0A=
foo - Function signature:=0A=
  r =3D foo(fun,[fun_extra_args])=0A=
Required arguments:=0A=
  fun : call-back function=0A=
Optional arguments:=0A=
  fun_extra_args :=3D () input tuple=0A=
Return objects:=0A=
  r : float=0A=
Call-back functions:=0A=
  def fun(i): return r=0A=
  Required arguments:=0A=
    i : input int=0A=
  Return objects:=0A=
    r : float=0A=
=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; def f(i): return i*i=0A=
... =0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; print callback.foo(f)     =0A=
110.0=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; print callback.foo(lambda i:1)=0A=
11.0=0A=
=0A=
</PRE></DIV>
<P>In the above example F2PY was able to guess accurately the signature =
of a=20
call-back function. However, sometimes F2PY cannot establish the =
signature as=20
one would wish and then the signature of a call-back function must be =
modified=20
in the signature file manually. Namely, signature files may contain =
special=20
modules (the names of such modules contain a substring <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">__user__</SPAN></TT>) that collect various signatures of =
call-back=20
functions.  Callback arguments in routine signatures have attribute <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">external</SPAN></TT> (see also <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =

class=3D"pre">intent(callback)</SPAN></TT> attribute).  To relate a =
callback=20
argument and its signature in <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">__user__</SPAN></TT> module block, use <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">use</SPAN></TT> statement as illustrated below. The same =
signature
 of a callback argument can be referred in different routine =
signatures.</P>
<DIV class=3D"topic">
<P class=3D"topic-title">Example</P>
<P>We use the same <A class=3D"reference" =
href=3D"https://sysbio.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/usersguide/callback.f">Fort=
ran=20
77 code</A> as in previous example but now we'll pretend that F2PY was =
not able=20
to guess the signatures of call-back arguments correctly. First, we =
create an=20
initial signature file <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">callback2.pyf</SPAN></TT> using F2PY:</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">f2py -m callback2 -h callback2.pyf =
callback.f=0A=
</PRE>
<P>Then modify it as follows</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">!    -*- f90 -*-=0A=
python module __user__routines =0A=
    interface=0A=
        function fun(i) result (r)=0A=
            integer :: i=0A=
            real*8 :: r=0A=
        end function fun=0A=
    end interface=0A=
end python module __user__routines=0A=
=0A=
python module callback2=0A=
    interface=0A=
        subroutine foo(f,r)=0A=
            use __user__routines, f=3D&gt;fun=0A=
            external f=0A=
            real*8 intent(out) :: r=0A=
        end subroutine foo=0A=
    end interface =0A=
end python module callback2=0A=
=0A=
</PRE>
<P>Finally, build the extension module using:</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">f2py -c callback2.pyf callback.f=0A=
</PRE>
<P>An example Python session would be identical to the previous example =
except=20
that argument names would differ.</P></DIV>
<P>Sometimes a Fortran package may require that users provide routines =
that the=20
package will use. F2PY can construct an interface to such routines so =
that=20
Python functions could be called from Fortran.</P>
<DIV class=3D"topic">
<P class=3D"topic-title">Example</P>
<P>Consider the following <A class=3D"reference" =
href=3D"https://sysbio.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/usersguide/calculate.f">For=
tran=20
77 subroutine</A> that takes an array and applies a function <TT=20
class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">func</SPAN></TT> to its =
elements.</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">      subroutine calculate(x,n)=0A=
cf2py intent(callback) func=0A=
      external func=0A=
c     The following lines define the signature of func for F2PY:=0A=
cf2py real*8 y=0A=
cf2py y =3D func(y)=0A=
c=0A=
cf2py intent(in,out,copy) x=0A=
      integer n,i=0A=
      real*8 x(n)=0A=
      do i=3D1,n=0A=
         x(i) =3D func(x(i))=0A=
      end do=0A=
      end=0A=
=0A=
</PRE>
<P>It is expected that function <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">func</SPAN></TT> has been defined externally. In order to =
use a=20
Python function as <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">func</SPAN></TT>, it=20
must have an attribute <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">intent(callback)</SPAN></TT> (it must be specified before =
the <TT=20
class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">external</SPAN></TT> =
statement).</P>
<P>Finally, build an extension module using:</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">f2py -c -m foo calculate.f=0A=
</PRE>
<P>In Python:</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">&gt;&gt;&gt; import foo=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; foo.calculate(range(5), lambda x: x*x)=0A=
array([  0.,   1.,   4.,   9.,  16.])=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; import math=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; foo.calculate(range(5), math.exp)=0A=
array([  1.        ,   2.71828175,   7.38905621,  20.08553696,  =
54.59814835])=0A=
=0A=
</PRE></DIV>
<P>F2PY generated interface is very flexible with respect to call-back
 arguments.  For each call-back argument an additional optional argument =
<TT=20
class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">&lt;name&gt;_extra_args</SPAN></TT> is=20
introduced by F2PY. This argument can be used to pass extra arguments to =
user=20
provided call-back arguments.</P>
<P>If a F2PY generated wrapper function expects the following call-back
 argument:</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">def fun(a_1,...,a_n):=0A=
   ...=0A=
   return x_1,...,x_k=0A=
</PRE>
<P>but the following Python function</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">def gun(b_1,...,b_m):=0A=
   ...=0A=
   return y_1,...,y_l=0A=
</PRE>
<P>is provided by an user, and in addition,</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">fun_extra_args =3D (e_1,...,e_p)=0A=
</PRE>
<P>is used, then the following rules are applied when a Fortran or C =
function=20
calls the call-back argument <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">gun</SPAN></TT>:</P>
<UL class=3D"simple">
  <LI>If <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">p=3D=3D0</SPAN></TT> =
then <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">gun(a_1,...,a_q)</SPAN></TT> is called, here <TT=20
  class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">q=3Dmin(m,n)</SPAN></TT>.</LI>
  <LI>If <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">n+p&lt;=3Dm</SPAN></TT> then <TT=20
  class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">gun(a_1,...,a_n,e_1,...,e_p)</SPAN></TT> is=20
  called.</LI>
  <LI>If <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">p&lt;=3Dm&lt;n+p</SPAN></TT> then=20
  <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">gun(a_1,...,a_q,e_1,...,e_p)</SPAN></TT>=20
  is called, here <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">q=3Dm-p</SPAN></TT>.</LI>
  <LI>If <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">p&gt;m</SPAN></TT> =
then <TT=20
  class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">gun(e_1,...,e_m)</SPAN></TT> is =
called.</LI>
  <LI>If <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">n+p</SPAN></TT> is =
less than the=20
  number of required arguments to <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">gun</SPAN></TT> then an exception is raised.</LI></UL>
<P>The function <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">gun</SPAN></TT> may return=20
any number of objects as a tuple. Then following rules are applied:</P>
<UL class=3D"simple">
  <LI>If <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">k&lt;l</SPAN></TT>, =
then <TT=20
  class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">y_{k+1},...,y_l</SPAN></TT> are=20
ignored.</LI>
  <LI>If <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">k&gt;l</SPAN></TT>, =
then only <TT=20
  class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">x_1,...,x_l</SPAN></TT> are=20
set.</LI></UL></DIV>
<DIV class=3D"section" id=3D"common-blocks">
<H2><A name=3D"common-blocks" class=3D"toc-backref" =
href=3D"https://sysbio.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/usersguide/#id37">4.5=A0=A0=
=A0Common=20
blocks</A></H2>
<P>F2PY generates wrappers to <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">common</SPAN></TT> blocks defined in a routine signature =
block.=20
Common blocks are visible by all Fortran codes linked with the current =
extension=20
module, but not to other extension modules (this restriction is due to =
how=20
Python imports shared libraries).  In Python, the F2PY wrappers to <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">common</SPAN></TT> blocks are <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">fortran</SPAN></TT> type objects that have (dynamic) =
attributes=20
related to data members of common blocks. When accessed, these =
attributes return=20
as Numeric array objects (multi-dimensional arrays are =
Fortran-contiguous) that
 directly link to data members in common blocks. Data members can be =
changed by=20
direct assignment or by in-place changes to the corresponding array =
objects.</P>
<DIV class=3D"topic">
<P class=3D"topic-title">Example</P>
<P>Consider the following <A class=3D"reference" =
href=3D"https://sysbio.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/usersguide/common.f">Fortra=
n=20
77 code</A></P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">C FILE: COMMON.F=0A=
      SUBROUTINE FOO=0A=
      INTEGER I,X=0A=
      REAL A=0A=
      COMMON /DATA/ I,X(4),A(2,3)=0A=
      PRINT*, "I=3D",I=0A=
      PRINT*, "X=3D[",X,"]"=0A=
      PRINT*, "A=3D["=0A=
      PRINT*, "[",A(1,1),",",A(1,2),",",A(1,3),"]"=0A=
      PRINT*, "[",A(2,1),",",A(2,2),",",A(2,3),"]"=0A=
      PRINT*, "]"=0A=
      END=0A=
C END OF COMMON.F=0A=
=0A=
</PRE>
<P>and wrap it using <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">f2py</SPAN> <SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">-c</SPAN> <SPAN class=3D"pre">-m</SPAN> <SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">common</SPAN> <SPAN =
class=3D"pre">common.f</SPAN></TT>.</P>
<P>In Python:</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">&gt;&gt;&gt; import common=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; print common.data.__doc__=0A=
i - 'i'-scalar=0A=
x - 'i'-array(4)=0A=
a - 'f'-array(2,3)=0A=
=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; common.data.i =3D 5=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; common.data.x[1] =3D 2 =0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; common.data.a =3D [[1,2,3],[4,5,6]]=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; common.foo()=0A=
 I=3D 5=0A=
 X=3D[ 0 2 0 0]=0A=
 A=3D[=0A=
 [  1.,  2.,  3.]=0A=
 [  4.,  5.,  6.]=0A=
 ]=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; common.data.a[1] =3D 45=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; common.foo()=0A=
 I=3D 5=0A=
 X=3D[ 0 2 0 0]=0A=
 A=3D[=0A=
 [  1.,  2.,  3.]=0A=
 [  45.,  45.,  45.]=0A=
 ]=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; common.data.a                 # a is Fortran-contiguous=0A=
array([[  1.,   2.,   3.],=0A=
       [ 45.,  45.,  45.]],'f')=0A=
=0A=
</PRE></DIV></DIV>
<DIV class=3D"section" id=3D"fortran-90-module-data">
<H2><A name=3D"fortran-90-module-data" class=3D"toc-backref" =
href=3D"https://sysbio.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/usersguide/#id38">4.6=A0=A0=
=A0Fortran=20
90 module data</A></H2>
<P>The F2PY interface to Fortran 90 module data is similar to Fortran 77 =
common=20
blocks.</P>
<DIV class=3D"topic">
<P class=3D"topic-title">Example</P>
<P>Consider the following <A class=3D"reference" =
href=3D"https://sysbio.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/usersguide/moddata.f90">For=
tran=20
90 code</A></P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">module mod=0A=
  integer i=0A=
  integer :: x(4)=0A=
  real, dimension(2,3) :: a=0A=
  real, allocatable, dimension(:,:) :: b =0A=
contains=0A=
  subroutine foo=0A=
    integer k=0A=
    print*, "i=3D",i=0A=
    print*, "x=3D[",x,"]"=0A=
    print*, "a=3D["=0A=
    print*, "[",a(1,1),",",a(1,2),",",a(1,3),"]"=0A=
    print*, "[",a(2,1),",",a(2,2),",",a(2,3),"]"=0A=
    print*, "]"=0A=
    print*, "Setting a(1,2)=3Da(1,2)+3"=0A=
    a(1,2) =3D a(1,2)+3=0A=
  end subroutine foo=0A=
end module mod=0A=
=0A=
</PRE>
<P>and wrap it using <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">f2py</SPAN> <SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">-c</SPAN> <SPAN class=3D"pre">-m</SPAN> <SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">moddata</SPAN> <SPAN =
class=3D"pre">moddata.f90</SPAN></TT>.</P>
<P>In Python:</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">&gt;&gt;&gt; import moddata=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; print moddata.mod.__doc__=0A=
i - 'i'-scalar=0A=
x - 'i'-array(4)=0A=
a - 'f'-array(2,3)=0A=
foo - Function signature:=0A=
  foo()=0A=
=0A=
=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; moddata.mod.i =3D 5  =0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; moddata.mod.x[:2] =3D [1,2]=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; moddata.mod.a =3D [[1,2,3],[4,5,6]]=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; moddata.mod.foo()                =0A=
 i=3D           5=0A=
 x=3D[           1           2           0           0 ]=0A=
 a=3D[=0A=
 [   1.000000     ,   2.000000     ,   3.000000     ]=0A=
 [   4.000000     ,   5.000000     ,   6.000000     ]=0A=
 ]=0A=
 Setting a(1,2)=3Da(1,2)+3=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; moddata.mod.a               # a is Fortran-contiguous=0A=
array([[ 1.,  5.,  3.],=0A=
       [ 4.,  5.,  6.]],'f')=0A=
=0A=
</PRE></DIV>
<DIV class=3D"section" id=3D"allocatable-arrays">
<H3><A name=3D"allocatable-arrays" class=3D"toc-backref" =
href=3D"https://sysbio.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/usersguide/#id39">4.6.1=A0=A0=
=A0Allocatable=20
arrays</A></H3>
<P>F2PY has basic support for Fortran 90 module allocatable arrays.</P>
<DIV class=3D"topic">
<P class=3D"topic-title">Example</P>
<P>Consider the following <A class=3D"reference" =
href=3D"https://sysbio.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/usersguide/allocarr.f90">Fo=
rtran=20
90 code</A></P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">module mod=0A=
  real, allocatable, dimension(:,:) :: b =0A=
contains=0A=
  subroutine foo=0A=
    integer k=0A=
    if (allocated(b)) then=0A=
       print*, "b=3D["=0A=
       do k =3D 1,size(b,1)=0A=
          print*, b(k,1:size(b,2))=0A=
       enddo=0A=
       print*, "]"=0A=
    else=0A=
       print*, "b is not allocated"=0A=
    endif=0A=
  end subroutine foo=0A=
end module mod=0A=
=0A=
</PRE>
<P>and wrap it using <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">f2py</SPAN> <SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">-c</SPAN> <SPAN class=3D"pre">-m</SPAN> <SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">allocarr</SPAN> <SPAN =
class=3D"pre">allocarr.f90</SPAN></TT>.</P>
<P>In Python:</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">&gt;&gt;&gt; import allocarr =0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; print allocarr.mod.__doc__=0A=
b - 'f'-array(-1,-1), not allocated=0A=
foo - Function signature:=0A=
  foo()=0A=
=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; allocarr.mod.foo()  =0A=
 b is not allocated=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; allocarr.mod.b =3D [[1,2,3],[4,5,6]]         # =
allocate/initialize b=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; allocarr.mod.foo()=0A=
 b=3D[=0A=
   1.000000       2.000000       3.000000    =0A=
   4.000000       5.000000       6.000000    =0A=
 ]=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; allocarr.mod.b                             # b is =
Fortran-contiguous=0A=
array([[ 1.,  2.,  3.],=0A=
       [ 4.,  5.,  6.]],'f')=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; allocarr.mod.b =3D [[1,2,3],[4,5,6],[7,8,9]] # =
reallocate/initialize b=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; allocarr.mod.foo()=0A=
 b=3D[=0A=
   1.000000       2.000000       3.000000    =0A=
   4.000000       5.000000       6.000000    =0A=
   7.000000       8.000000       9.000000    =0A=
 ]=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; allocarr.mod.b =3D None                      # deallocate =
array=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; allocarr.mod.foo()=0A=
 b is not allocated=0A=
=0A=
</PRE></DIV></DIV></DIV></DIV>
<DIV class=3D"section" id=3D"using-f2py">
<H1><A name=3D"using-f2py" class=3D"toc-backref" =
href=3D"https://sysbio.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/usersguide/#id40">5=A0=A0=A0=
Using=20
F2PY</A></H1>
<P>F2PY can be used either as a command line tool <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">f2py</SPAN></TT> or as a Python module <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">f2py2e</SPAN></TT>.</P>
<DIV class=3D"section" id=3D"command-f2py">
<H2><A name=3D"command-f2py" class=3D"toc-backref" =
href=3D"https://sysbio.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/usersguide/#id41">5.1=A0=A0=
=A0Command=20
<TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">f2py</SPAN></TT></A></H2>
<P>When used as a command line tool, <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">f2py</SPAN></TT> has three major modes, distinguished by =
the usage=20
of <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">-c</SPAN></TT> and <TT=20
class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">-h</SPAN></TT> switches:</P>
<OL class=3D"arabic simple">
  <LI>To scan Fortran sources and generate a signature file, =
use</LI></OL>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">f2py -h &lt;filename.pyf&gt; =
&lt;options&gt; &lt;fortran files&gt;   \=0A=
  [[ only: &lt;fortran functions&gt;  : ]                \=0A=
   [ skip: &lt;fortran functions&gt;  : ]]...            \=0A=
  [&lt;fortran files&gt; ...]=0A=
</PRE>
  <P>Note that a Fortran source file can contain many routines, and not
   necessarily all routines are needed to be used from Python. So, you =
can=20
  either specify which routines should be wrapped (in <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">only:</SPAN> <SPAN class=3D"pre">..</SPAN> <SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">:</SPAN></TT> part) or which routines F2PY should =
ignored (in <TT=20
  class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">skip:</SPAN> <SPAN =
class=3D"pre">..</SPAN>=20
  <SPAN class=3D"pre">:</SPAN></TT> part).</P>
  <P>If <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">&lt;filename.pyf&gt;</SPAN></TT>=20
  is specified as <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">stdout</SPAN></TT> then=20
  signatures are send to standard output instead of a file.</P>
  <P>Among other options (see below), the following options can be used =
in this=20
  mode:</P>
  <DL>
    <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
    class=3D"pre">--overwrite-signature</SPAN></TT></DT>
    <DD>Overwrite existing signature file.</DD></DL></BLOCKQUOTE>
<OL class=3D"arabic simple" start=3D"2">
  <LI>To construct an extension module, use</LI></OL>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">f2py &lt;options&gt; &lt;fortran files&gt;  =
        \=0A=
  [[ only: &lt;fortran functions&gt;  : ]     \=0A=
   [ skip: &lt;fortran functions&gt;  : ]]... \=0A=
  [&lt;fortran files&gt; ...]=0A=
</PRE>
  <P>The constructed extension module is saved as <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">&lt;modulename&gt;module.c</SPAN></TT> to the current=20
  directory.</P>
  <P>Here <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">&lt;fortran</SPAN> =
<SPAN class=3D"pre">files&gt;</SPAN></TT>=20
  may also contain signature files. Among other options (see below), the =

  following options can be used in this mode:</P>
  <DL>
    <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">--debug-capi</SPAN></TT></DT>
    <DD>Add debugging hooks to the extension module. When using this =
extension=20
    module, various information about the wrapper is printed to standard =
output,=20
    for example, the values of variables, the steps taken, etc.</DD>
    <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
    class=3D"pre">-include'&lt;includefile&gt;'</SPAN></TT></DT>
    <DD>
    <P class=3D"first">Add a CPP <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
    class=3D"pre">#include</SPAN></TT> statement to the extension module =
source.=20
    <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">&lt;includefile&gt;</SPAN></TT> should=20
    be given in one of the following forms:</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">"filename.ext"=0A=
&lt;filename.ext&gt;=0A=
</PRE>
    <P>The include statement is inserted just before the wrapper =
functions. This=20
    feature enables using arbitrary C functions (defined in <TT=20
    class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">&lt;includefile&gt;</SPAN></TT>) in F2PY=20
    generated wrappers.</P>
    <P class=3D"last">This option is deprecated. Use <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
    class=3D"pre">usercode</SPAN></TT> statement to specify C codelets =
directly in=20
    signature filess</P></DD></DL>
  <P><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">--[no-]wrap-functions</SPAN></TT></P>
  <BLOCKQUOTE>Create Fortran subroutine wrappers to Fortran functions. =
<TT=20
    class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">--wrap-functions</SPAN></TT> =
is default=20
    because it ensures maximum portability and compiler =
independence.</BLOCKQUOTE>
  <DL>
    <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">--include-paths</SPAN> =
<SPAN=20
    class=3D"pre">&lt;path1&gt;:&lt;path2&gt;:..</SPAN></TT></DT>
    <DD>Search include files from given directories.</DD>
    <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">--help-link</SPAN> =
<SPAN class=3D"pre">[&lt;list</SPAN>=20
    <SPAN class=3D"pre">of</SPAN> <SPAN class=3D"pre">resources</SPAN> =
<SPAN class=3D"pre">names&gt;]</SPAN></TT>=20
    </DT>
    <DD>List system resources found by <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
    class=3D"pre">scipy_distutils/system_info.py</SPAN></TT>. For =
example, try <TT=20
    class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">f2py</SPAN> <SPAN=20
    class=3D"pre">--help-link</SPAN> <SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">lapack_opt</SPAN></TT>.</DD></DL></BLOCKQUOTE>
<OL class=3D"arabic simple" start=3D"3">
  <LI>To build an extension module, use</LI></OL>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">f2py -c &lt;options&gt; &lt;fortran =
files&gt;       \=0A=
  [[ only: &lt;fortran functions&gt;  : ]     \=0A=
   [ skip: &lt;fortran functions&gt;  : ]]... \=0A=
  [ &lt;fortran/c source files&gt; ] [ &lt;.o, .a, .so files&gt; ]=0A=
</PRE>
  <P>If <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">&lt;fortran</SPAN> =
<SPAN class=3D"pre">files&gt;</SPAN></TT>=20
  contains a signature file, then a source for an extension module is=20
  constructed, all Fortran and C sources are compiled, and finally all =
object=20
  and library files are linked to the extension module <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">&lt;modulename&gt;.so</SPAN></TT> which is saved into =
the current
   directory.</P>
  <P>If <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">&lt;fortran</SPAN> =
<SPAN class=3D"pre">files&gt;</SPAN></TT>=20
  does not contain a signature file, then an extension module is =
constructed by=20
  scanning all Fortran source codes for routine signatures.</P>
  <P>Among other options (see below) and options described in previous =
mode, the=20
  following options can be used in this mode:</P>
  <DL>
    <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">--help-fcompiler</SPAN></TT></DT>
    <DD>List available Fortran compilers.</DD>
    <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">--help-compiler</SPAN></TT>=20
    [depreciated]</DT>
    <DD>List available Fortran compilers.</DD>
    <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
    class=3D"pre">--fcompiler=3D&lt;Vendor&gt;</SPAN></TT></DT>
    <DD>Specify Fortran compiler type by vendor.</DD>
    <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
    class=3D"pre">--f77exec=3D&lt;path&gt;</SPAN></TT></DT>
    <DD>Specify the path to F77 compiler</DD>
    <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
    class=3D"pre">--fcompiler-exec=3D&lt;path&gt;</SPAN></TT> =
[depreciated]</DT>
    <DD>Specify the path to F77 compiler</DD>
    <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
    class=3D"pre">--f90exec=3D&lt;path&gt;</SPAN></TT></DT>
    <DD>Specify the path to F90 compiler</DD>
    <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
    class=3D"pre">--f90compiler-exec=3D&lt;path&gt;</SPAN></TT> =
[depreciated]</DT>
    <DD>Specify the path to F90 compiler</DD>
    <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
    class=3D"pre">--f77flags=3D&lt;string&gt;</SPAN></TT></DT>
    <DD>Specify F77 compiler flags</DD>
    <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
    class=3D"pre">--f90flags=3D&lt;string&gt;</SPAN></TT></DT>
    <DD>Specify F90 compiler flags</DD>
    <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
    class=3D"pre">--opt=3D&lt;string&gt;</SPAN></TT></DT>
    <DD>Specify optimization flags</DD>
    <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
    class=3D"pre">--arch=3D&lt;string&gt;</SPAN></TT></DT>
    <DD>Specify architecture specific optimization flags</DD>
    <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">--noopt</SPAN></TT></DT>
    <DD>Compile without optimization</DD>
    <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">--noarch</SPAN></TT></DT>
    <DD>Compile without arch-dependent optimization</DD>
    <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">--debug</SPAN></TT></DT>
    <DD>Compile with debugging information</DD>
    <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">-l&lt;libname&gt;</SPAN></TT></DT>
    <DD>Use the library <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
    class=3D"pre">&lt;libname&gt;</SPAN></TT> when linking.</DD>
    <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
    class=3D"pre">-D&lt;macro&gt;[=3D&lt;defn=3D1&gt;]</SPAN></TT></DT>
    <DD>Define macro <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
    class=3D"pre">&lt;macro&gt;</SPAN></TT> as <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">&lt;defn&gt;</SPAN></TT>.</DD>
    <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">-U&lt;macro&gt;</SPAN></TT></DT>
    <DD>Define macro <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
    class=3D"pre">&lt;macro&gt;</SPAN></TT></DD>
    <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">-I&lt;dir&gt;</SPAN></TT></DT>
    <DD>Append directory <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
    class=3D"pre">&lt;dir&gt;</SPAN></TT> to the list of directories =
searched for
     include files.</DD>
    <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">-L&lt;dir&gt;</SPAN></TT></DT>
    <DD>Add directory <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
    class=3D"pre">&lt;dir&gt;</SPAN></TT> to the list of directories to  =
be =20
    searched for <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">-l</SPAN></TT>.</DD></DL>
  <P><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">link-&lt;resource&gt;</SPAN></TT></P>
  <BLOCKQUOTE>Link extension module with &lt;resource&gt; as defined by =
<TT=20
    class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
    class=3D"pre">scipy_distutils/system_info.py</SPAN></TT>. E.g. to =
link with=20
    optimized LAPACK libraries (vecLib on MacOSX, ATLAS elsewhere), use =
<TT=20
    class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">--link-lapack_opt</SPAN></TT>. =
See also=20
    <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">--help-link</SPAN></TT>=20
  switch.</BLOCKQUOTE>
  <P>When building an extension module, a combination of the following =
macros=20
  may be required for non-gcc Fortran compilers:</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">-DPREPEND_FORTRAN=0A=
-DNO_APPEND_FORTRAN=0A=
-DUPPERCASE_FORTRAN=0A=
</PRE>
  <P>To test the performance of F2PY generated interfaces, use <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">-DF2PY_REPORT_ATEXIT</SPAN></TT>. Then a report of =
various timings=20
  is printed out at the exit of Python. This feature may not work on all =

  platforms, currently only Linux platform is supported.</P>
  <P>To see whether F2PY generated interface performs copies of array =
arguments,=20
  use <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">-DF2PY_REPORT_ON_ARRAY_COPY=3D&lt;int&gt;</SPAN></TT>. =
When the size
   of an array argument is larger than <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">&lt;int&gt;</SPAN></TT>, a message about the coping is =
sent to <TT=20
  class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">stderr</SPAN></TT>.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Other options:</P>
<DL>
  <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">-m</SPAN> <SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">&lt;modulename&gt;</SPAN></TT></DT>
  <DD>Name of an extension module. Default is <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">untitled</SPAN></TT>.</DD>
  <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">--[no-]lower</SPAN></TT></DT>
  <DD>Do [not] lower the cases in <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">&lt;fortran</SPAN> <SPAN =
class=3D"pre">files&gt;</SPAN></TT>.  By=20
  default, <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">--lower</SPAN></TT> =
is assumed=20
  with <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">-h</SPAN></TT> switch, =
and <TT=20
  class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">--no-lower</SPAN></TT> without =
the <TT=20
  class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">-h</SPAN></TT> switch.</DD>
  <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">--build-dir</SPAN> <SPAN =

  class=3D"pre">&lt;dirname&gt;</SPAN></TT></DT>
  <DD>All F2PY generated files are created in <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">&lt;dirname&gt;</SPAN></TT>.=20
   Default is <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">tempfile.mktemp()</SPAN></TT>.</DD>
  <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">--quiet</SPAN></TT></DT>
  <DD>Run quietly.</DD>
  <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">--verbose</SPAN></TT></DT>
  <DD>Run with extra verbosity.</DD>
  <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">-v</SPAN></TT></DT>
  <DD>Print f2py version ID and exit.</DD></DL>
<P>Execute <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">f2py</SPAN></TT> =
without any=20
options to get an up-to-date list of available options.</P></DIV>
<DIV class=3D"section" id=3D"python-module-f2py2e">
<H2><A name=3D"python-module-f2py2e" class=3D"toc-backref" =
href=3D"https://sysbio.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/usersguide/#id42">5.2=A0=A0=
=A0Python=20
module <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">f2py2e</SPAN></TT></A></H2>
<DIV class=3D"topic">
<P class=3D"topic-title">Warning</P>
<P>The current Python interface to <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">f2py2e</SPAN></TT> module is not mature and may change in =
future=20
depending on users needs.</P></DIV>
<P>The following functions are provided by the <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">f2py2e</SPAN></TT>=20
module:</P>
<DL>
  <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">run_main(&lt;list&gt;)</SPAN></TT></DT>
  <DD>
  <P class=3D"first">Equivalent to running:</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">f2py &lt;args&gt;=0A=
</PRE>
  <P>where <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">&lt;args&gt;=3Dstring.join(&lt;list&gt;,'</SPAN> <SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">')</SPAN></TT>, but in Python.  Unless <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">-h</SPAN></TT> is used, this function returns a =
dictionary=20
  containing information on generated modules and their dependencies on =
source
   files.  For example, the command <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">f2py</SPAN> <SPAN class=3D"pre">-m</SPAN> <SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">scalar</SPAN> <SPAN class=3D"pre">scalar.f</SPAN></TT> =
can be
   executed from Python as follows</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">&gt;&gt;&gt; import f2py2e=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; =
r=3Df2py2e.run_main(['-m','scalar','docs/usersguide/scalar.f'])=0A=
Reading fortran codes...=0A=
        Reading file 'docs/usersguide/scalar.f'=0A=
Post-processing...=0A=
        Block: scalar=0A=
                        Block: FOO=0A=
Building modules...=0A=
        Building module "scalar"...=0A=
        Wrote C/API module "scalar" to file "./scalarmodule.c"=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; print r=0A=
{'scalar': {'h': =
['/home/users/pearu/src_cvs/f2py2e/src/fortranobject.h'],=0A=
	 'csrc': ['./scalarmodule.c', =0A=
                  =
'/home/users/pearu/src_cvs/f2py2e/src/fortranobject.c']}}=0A=
=0A=
</PRE>
  <P class=3D"last">You cannot build extension modules with this =
function, that=20
  is, using <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">-c</SPAN></TT> is =
not allowed.=20
  Use <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">compile</SPAN></TT> =
command instead,=20
  see below.</P></DD></DL>
<P><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">compile(source,</SPAN> =
<SPAN class=3D"pre">modulename=3D'untitled',</SPAN>=20
<SPAN class=3D"pre">extra_args=3D'',</SPAN> <SPAN =
class=3D"pre">verbose=3D1,</SPAN>=20
<SPAN class=3D"pre">source_fn=3DNone)</SPAN></TT></P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  <P>Build extension module from Fortran 77 source string <TT=20
  class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">source</SPAN></TT>.  Return 0 if =
successful.
   Note that this function actually calls <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">f2py</SPAN> <SPAN class=3D"pre">-c</SPAN> <SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">..</SPAN></TT> from shell to ensure safety of the =
current Python=20
  process. For example,</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">&gt;&gt;&gt; import f2py2e=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; fsource =3D '''=0A=
...       subroutine foo=0A=
...       print*, "Hello world!"=0A=
...       end =0A=
... '''=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; f2py2e.compile(fsource,modulename=3D'hello',verbose=3D0)=0A=
0=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; import hello=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; hello.foo()=0A=
 Hello world!=0A=
=0A=
</PRE></BLOCKQUOTE></DIV></DIV>
<DIV class=3D"section" id=3D"using-scipy-distutils">
<H1><A name=3D"using-scipy-distutils" class=3D"toc-backref" =
href=3D"https://sysbio.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/usersguide/#id43">6=A0=A0=A0=
Using=20
<TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">scipy_distutils</SPAN></TT></A></H1>
<P><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">scipy_distutils</SPAN></TT> =
is part of=20
the <A class=3D"reference" href=3D"http://www.scipy.org/">SciPy</A> =
project and aims=20
to extend standard Python <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">distutils</SPAN></TT> to deal with Fortran sources and =
F2PY
 signature files, e.g. compile Fortran sources, call F2PY to construct =
extension=20
modules, etc.</P>
<DIV class=3D"topic">
<P class=3D"topic-title">Example</P>
<P>Consider the following <A class=3D"reference" =
href=3D"https://sysbio.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/usersguide/setup_example.py=
">setup=20
file</A>:</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">#!/usr/bin/env python=0A=
# File: setup_example.py=0A=
=0A=
from scipy_distutils.core import Extension=0A=
=0A=
ext1 =3D Extension(name =3D 'scalar',=0A=
                 sources =3D ['scalar.f'])=0A=
ext2 =3D Extension(name =3D 'fib2',=0A=
                 sources =3D ['fib2.pyf','fib1.f'])=0A=
=0A=
if __name__ =3D=3D "__main__":=0A=
    from scipy_distutils.core import setup=0A=
    setup(name =3D 'f2py_example',=0A=
          description       =3D "F2PY Users Guide examples",=0A=
          author            =3D "Pearu Peterson",=0A=
          author_email      =3D "pearu@cens.ioc.ee",=0A=
          ext_modules =3D [ext1,ext2]=0A=
          )=0A=
# End of setup_example.py=0A=
=0A=
</PRE>
<P>Running</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">python setup_example.py build=0A=
</PRE>
<P>will build two extension modules <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">scalar</SPAN></TT> and <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">fib2</SPAN></TT> to the build directory.</P></DIV>
<P><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">scipy_distutils</SPAN></TT> =
extends <TT=20
class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">distutils</SPAN></TT> with the =
following=20
features:</P>
<UL>
  <LI>
  <P class=3D"first"><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">Extension</SPAN></TT>=20
  class argument <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">sources</SPAN></TT> may=20
  contain Fortran source files. In addition, the list <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">sources</SPAN></TT> may contain at most one F2PY =
signature file,=20
  and then the name of an Extension module must match with the <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">&lt;modulename&gt;</SPAN></TT> used in signature file.  =
It is
   assumed that an F2PY signature file contains exactly one <TT=20
  class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">python</SPAN> <SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">module</SPAN></TT> block.</P>
  <P>If <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">sources</SPAN></TT> =
does not=20
  contain a signature files, then F2PY is used to scan Fortran source =
files for=20
  routine signatures to construct the wrappers to Fortran codes.</P>
  <P>Additional options to F2PY process can be given using <TT=20
  class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">Extension</SPAN></TT> class =
argument <TT=20
  class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">f2py_options</SPAN></TT>.</P></LI></UL>
<DIV class=3D"section" id=3D"scipy-distutils-0-2-2-and-up">
<H2><A name=3D"scipy-distutils-0-2-2-and-up" class=3D"toc-backref" =
href=3D"https://sysbio.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/usersguide/#id44">6.1=A0=A0=
&#65533;<TT=20
class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">scipy_distutils</SPAN></TT> 0.2.2 =
and=20
up</A></H2>
<UL>
  <LI>
  <P class=3D"first">The following new <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">distutils</SPAN></TT> commands are defined:</P>
  <DL>
    <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">build_src</SPAN></TT></DT>
    <DD>
    <P class=3D"first last">to construct Fortran wrapper extension =
modules, among=20
    many other things.</P></DD>
    <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">config_fc</SPAN></TT></DT>
    <DD>
    <P class=3D"first last">to change Fortran compiler =
options</P></DD></DL>
  <P>as well as <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">build_ext</SPAN></TT> and =20
  <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">build_clib</SPAN></TT> =
commands are=20
  enhanced  to support Fortran sources.</P>
  <P>Run</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">python &lt;setup.py file&gt; config_fc =
build_src build_ext --help=0A=
</PRE>
  <P>to see available options for these commands.</P></LI>
  <LI>
  <P class=3D"first">When building Python packages containing Fortran =
sources,=20
  then one can choose different Fortran compilers by using <TT=20
  class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">build_ext</SPAN></TT> command =
option <TT=20
  class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">--fcompiler=3D&lt;Vendor&gt;</SPAN></TT>. Here=20
  <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">&lt;Vendor&gt;</SPAN></TT> =
can be one of=20
  the following names:</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">absoft sun mips intel intelv intele intelev =
nag compaq compaqv gnu vast pg hpux=0A=
</PRE>
  <P>See <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">scipy_distutils/fcompiler.py</SPAN></TT> for up-to-date =
list of
   supported compilers or run</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">f2py -c --help-fcompiler=0A=
</PRE></LI></UL></DIV>
<DIV class=3D"section" id=3D"scipy-distutils-pre-0-2-2">
<H2><A name=3D"scipy-distutils-pre-0-2-2" class=3D"toc-backref" =
href=3D"https://sysbio.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/usersguide/#id45">6.2=A0=A0=
&#65533;<TT=20
class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">scipy_distutils</SPAN></TT> pre =
0.2.2</A></H2>
<UL>
  <LI>
  <P class=3D"first">The following new <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">distutils</SPAN></TT> commands are defined:</P>
  <DL>
    <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">build_flib</SPAN></TT></DT>
    <DD>
    <P class=3D"first last">to build f77/f90 libraries used by Python=20
    extensions;</P></DD>
    <DT><TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">run_f2py</SPAN></TT></DT>
    <DD>
    <P class=3D"first last">to construct Fortran wrapper extension=20
    modules.</P></DD></DL>
  <P>Run</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">python &lt;setup.py file&gt; build_flib =
run_f2py --help=0A=
</PRE>
  <P>to see available options for these commands.</P></LI>
  <LI>
  <P class=3D"first">When building Python packages containing Fortran =
sources,=20
  then one can choose different Fortran compilers either by using <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">build_flib</SPAN></TT> command option <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">--fcompiler=3D&lt;Vendor&gt;</SPAN></TT> or by defining =
environment
   variable <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">FC_VENDOR=3D&lt;Vendor&gt;</SPAN></TT>. Here <TT=20
  class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">&lt;Vendor&gt;</SPAN></TT> can =
be one of the
   following names:</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">Absoft Sun SGI Intel Itanium NAG Compaq =
Digital Gnu VAST PG=0A=
</PRE>
  <P>See <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
  class=3D"pre">scipy_distutils/command/build_flib.py</SPAN></TT> for =
up-to-date=20
  list of supported compilers.</P></LI></UL></DIV></DIV>
<DIV class=3D"section" id=3D"extended-f2py-usages">
<H1><A name=3D"extended-f2py-usages" class=3D"toc-backref" =
href=3D"https://sysbio.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/usersguide/#id46">7=A0=A0=A0=
Extended=20
F2PY usages</A></H1>
<DIV class=3D"section" =
id=3D"adding-self-written-functions-to-f2py-generated-modules">
<H2><A name=3D"adding-self-written-functions-to-f2py-generated-modules" =
class=3D"toc-backref"=20
href=3D"https://sysbio.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/usersguide/#id47">7.1=A0=A0=
=A0Adding=20
self-written functions to F2PY generated modules</A></H2>
<P>Self-written Python C/API functions can be defined inside signature =
files=20
using <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">usercode</SPAN></TT> and =
<TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">pymethoddef</SPAN></TT> statements (they must be used =
inside the <TT=20
class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">python</SPAN> <SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">module</SPAN></TT> block). For example, the following =
signature file=20
<TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">spam.pyf</SPAN></TT></P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">!    -*- f90 -*-=0A=
python module spam=0A=
    usercode '''=0A=
  static char doc_spam_system[] =3D "Execute a shell command.";=0A=
  static PyObject *spam_system(PyObject *self, PyObject *args)=0A=
  {=0A=
    char *command;=0A=
    int sts;=0A=
=0A=
    if (!PyArg_ParseTuple(args, "s", &amp;command))=0A=
        return NULL;=0A=
    sts =3D system(command);=0A=
    return Py_BuildValue("i", sts);=0A=
  }=0A=
    '''=0A=
    pymethoddef '''=0A=
    {"system",  spam_system, METH_VARARGS, doc_spam_system},=0A=
    '''=0A=
end python module spam=0A=
=0A=
</PRE>
<P>wraps the C library function <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">system()</SPAN></TT>:</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">f2py -c spam.pyf=0A=
</PRE>
<P>In Python:</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">&gt;&gt;&gt; import spam=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; status =3D spam.system('whoami')=0A=
pearu=0A=
&gt;&gt; status =3D spam.system('blah')=0A=
sh: line 1: blah: command not found=0A=
</PRE></DIV>
<DIV class=3D"section" =
id=3D"modifying-the-dictionary-of-a-f2py-generated-module">
<H2><A name=3D"modifying-the-dictionary-of-a-f2py-generated-module" =
class=3D"toc-backref"=20
href=3D"https://sysbio.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/usersguide/#id48">7.2=A0=A0=
=A0Modifying the=20
dictionary of a F2PY generated module</A></H2>
<P>The following example illustrates how to add an user-defined =
variables to a=20
F2PY generated extension module. Given the following signature file</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">!    -*- f90 -*-=0A=
python module var=0A=
  usercode '''=0A=
    int BAR =3D 5;=0A=
  '''=0A=
  interface=0A=
    usercode '''=0A=
      PyDict_SetItemString(d,"BAR",PyInt_FromLong(BAR));=0A=
    '''=0A=
  end interface=0A=
end python module=0A=
=0A=
</PRE>
<P>compile it as <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">f2py</SPAN> =
<SPAN class=3D"pre">-c</SPAN>=20
<SPAN class=3D"pre">var.pyf</SPAN></TT>.</P>
<P>Notice that the second <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">usercode</SPAN></TT> statement must be defined inside an =
<TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">interface</SPAN></TT> block and where the module =
dictionary is=20
available through the variable <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN=20
class=3D"pre">d</SPAN></TT> (see <TT class=3D"literal"><SPAN =
class=3D"pre">f2py</SPAN>=20
<SPAN class=3D"pre">var.pyf</SPAN></TT>-generated <TT =
class=3D"literal"><SPAN class=3D"pre">varmodule.c</SPAN></TT>=20
for additional details).</P>
<P>In Python:</P>
<PRE class=3D"literal-block">&gt;&gt;&gt; import var=0A=
&gt;&gt;&gt; var.BAR=0A=
5=0A=
</PRE><!-- References=0A=
=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D -->=20
</DIV></DIV></DIV>
